"My most recent collaboration, for example, is a Work In Progress typography collaboration with independent brand designer Juli Vignette, where she has taken illustrations that focus on female creativity from different women around the world, and is applying a relevant piece of text to each piece of work. It will be released between December and January." People would be surprised to know that despite Rachael's current drawing style, her passion for illustrations originally grew from Marvel Comic illustrations. What would most people be surprised to know about you? Comment below!

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1626209506396400011_4073479', 'hashtags': 'ShineTheory', 'caption': 'Who gets inspired by periods and pug puppies? Gemma Correll, known as @gemmacorrell. This England native likes to draw everyday people in their everyday lives. âA lot of my work comes from personal experience. I make comics and illustrations about my every day life, particularly concerning my struggles with anxiety â and also about being a woman in general â I have a lot to say about periods!â The 32-year-old also has two pugs: Mr. Pickles and Bella, whom she often features in her illustrations. If you want to have a great Instagram account, she offers this piece of advice: âBeing yourself is important. I put more personal work on Instagram than on any other social media or website. It\'s not always \'finished\' â sometimes, it\'s just a scribble from my sketchbook, but I think followers like to see things like that, and behind-the-scenes stuff. I try to vary my posts, so I\'ll have a pic of a new product, followed by a comic, followed by something from my sketchbook â and I post nearly every day. Also, it helps if you have cute pets.â Her proudest moment included the images she created for Mental Health America for its "mental illness feels like" campaigns in 2016 and 2017. If you want to have a great Instagram account, she offers this piece of advice: âBeing yourself is important. I put more personal work on Instagram than on any other social media or website. It's not always 'finished' â sometimes, it's just a scribble from my sketchbook, but I think followers like to see things like that, and behind-the-scenes stuff. I try to vary my posts, so I'll have a pic of a new product, followed by a comic, followed by something from my sketchbook â and I post nearly every day. Also, it helps if you have cute pets.â Her proudest moment included the images she created for Mental Health America for its "mental illness feels like" campaigns in 2016 and 2017. What is your proudest moment to date? â¤ï¸Comment below! #ShineTheory

There is something almost magical about how a woman perceives the world with power, vulnerability, elegance and wit. â¤ï¸ My mom is a huge motivation and inspiration, as she always pushed and encouraged me in whatever I wanted to do,â said 29-year-old @IonutRadulescu. This illustrator and designer is a Romanian native who left his hometown at an early age to move to the U.S. His Instagram feed is filled with bright colors, bold patterns and feminist-driven statements. â One of his biggest accomplishments to date was being awarded the Dean's Scholarship at SCAD (Savannah College of Art and Design). Instagram has been a platform for Ionut to showcase his work and collaborate with brands such as @hellomr and @refinery29. His advice for creating a great social game? âGetting your A-game in social is definitely a constant practice and work in progress. I begun to actively share my work in March 2014, and I treated Instagram as part visual diary, part portfolio. It all started with a daily doodle lettering project where I challenged myself to make an experiment each day, embracing freedom of expression and allowing myself to make mistakes. It was a great exercise of perseverance that eventually lead to an exhibition in NYC in 2016 where I showed a selection from over 600 artwork pieces created along the way.â #ShineTheory", 'comment_count': 49, 'like_count': 14321, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BZJQozHASMZ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/21689429_193608437846518_6623590274880765952_n.jpg'}

The Seattle native draws her inspiration from her day-to-day life and even though she only started her illustrating career two years ago, she\'s already amassed over 500k followers thanks to how her works of art are relatable to people of all ages. Currently living in NYC, Mari still compares her current drawings to her work as a 5-year-old, but reminds us that you can still be an artist without being very good at drawing. She offers this piece of advice: "find YOUR voice; don\'t use someone else\'s voice. It can take time to find your voice and develop your own style, but just getting in the habit of it will really help. If you write or draw, pretend you\'re creating something for your best friend rather than for \'an audience.\' That will help you to create from a place of authenticity and love." In short? Chloe can shred. âWhen I was 8 years old I went to Switzerland and really got into snowboarding. I was competing and starting to learn a lot of new tricks,â explains the athlete, who trains with the U.S. team. âI could never have imagined that I would get this far; it has all been a crazy and exciting adventure.â Chloe was selected as Team USAâs flag bearer for the 2016 Youth Olympic Games, where she took home two gold medals and became the highest scoring snowboarder in the history of the games at the time. Unsurprisingly, sheâs a favorite to take home Olympic gold in the 2018 PyeongChang Winter Games. âIâm honored that people have such high expectations for me. I try not to feel too much pressure and instead try to focus on taking care of my physical and mental health,â says Chloe. âA big priority for me is to eventually start a foundation that works with sick kids. We aren't born with equal rights, or afforded the same opportunities â we are undermined by strategic laws and government policy that segment and separate us by circumstances outside our control. The Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals policy was a significant effort that afforded young undocumented immigrants the chance to work, learn and thrive in the country they call home. President Trump rescinded #DACA this week, putting an estimated 790,000 young people at risk for deportation â some to countries they've never known. They stand to lose everything they have worked for, but we refuse to stay silent while families are ripped apart and young people's lives are put at risk. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1590723591832434607_4073479', 'hashtags': 'ShineTheory', 'caption': "This 26-year-old Amsterdam native loves adding color, playfulness, and femininity to her illustrations, which is why we are more than obsessed with @bodiljane. Sheâs collaborated with Blood Orange, Lady Gaga, and Wet, and her vocals can be heard on âInterlude: This Momentâ from Solangeâs A Seat at the Table. The North Carolina native, who grew up a Jehovahâs Witness, attended the North Carolina School for the Arts to study cello before dropping out after a year. âThe ocean is one of my favorite places to be. For me, playing the cello is like diving into the clearest of oceans with nothing on but my own skin,â she says. After leaving school, Lu, as she prefers to be called, started jamming with a local hip-hop group, through which she met Nappy Roots. She went on to play cello on one of the quartetâs albums, and toured with them on and off over the next two years before settling in New York, where she recorded her six-track debut EP called Church in 2016. Currently, Lu is finishing up the soundtrack for a short film by Tiana Marenah. âItâs really exciting for me, itâs a dream come true,â she says of the project. âTiana and I met though a collective weâre both part of called HowDoYouSayYamInAfrican. Soundtracking is tedious work, but itâs improving my skills as a producer, maneuvering around computer programs and such.â Though she remains tight-lipped about whether or not we can expect an album anytime soon, she has stellar advice in bounds: âHold on to your compass and donât let anyone else sway it for you. This process was once nearly impossible to DIY, but @Sally_Hansen's new chrome powder kit will be in drugstores soon to save the day! We asked their Global Color Ambassador @mpnails to teach us how to do a half-moon mirror many thatâs worthy of the the âgram. Hereâs how to get the reflective look.

1. Grab a pair of tweezers and position strips of tape halfway down your nails.
2. Paint the top half of your nails with two coats of Sally Hansen Miracle Gel in a dark shade.
3. Gently buff Gunmetal Salon Chrome Powder into the tacky polish for a mirror-like effect.
4. Use tweezers to peel off stripes of tape for a negative-space detail. 
5. Paint with Chrome Top Coat to seal in the shine.

column15:
If youâve ever watched mesmerizing chrome powder in action on Insta, you know that the result is a gorgeous mirror mani. This process was once nearly impossible to DIY, but @Sally_Hansen's new chrome powder kit will be in drugstores soon to save the day! We asked their Global Color Ambassador @mpnails to teach us how to do a half-moon mirror many thatâs worthy of the the âgram. Hereâs how to get the reflective look.

1. Grab a pair of tweezers and position strips of tape halfway down your nails.
2. Paint the top half of your nails with two coats of Sally Hansen Miracle Gel in a dark shade.
3. Gently buff Gunmetal Salon Chrome Powder into the tacky polish for a mirror-like effect.
4. Use tweezers to peel off stripes of tape for a negative-space detail. 
5. Paint with Chrome Top Coat to seal in the shine. 
6. Step back and admire the cool chrome.
column24:
video If youâve ever watched mesmerizing chrome powder in action on Insta, you know that the result is a gorgeous mirror mani. This process was once nearly impossible to DIY, but @Sally_Hansen's new chrome powder kit will be in drugstores soon to save the day! We asked their Global Color Ambassador @mpnails to teach us how to do a half-moon mirror many thatâs worthy of the the âgram. Hereâs how to get the reflective look.

1. Grab a pair of tweezers and position strips of tape halfway down your nails.
2. Paint the top half of your nails with two coats of Sally Hansen Miracle Gel in a dark shade.
3. Gently buff Gunmetal Salon Chrome Powder into the tacky polish for a mirror-like effect.
4. Use tweezers to peel off stripes of tape for a negative-space detail. 
5. Paint with Chrome Top Coat to seal in the shine. 
6. Step back and admire the cool chrome.

column24: photo At 16 years old, Alexis Franklin started her Instagram as a way to simply document her progress as an artist â sketching paintings of people that interest her and pulling inspiration from everything in her everyday life. Now, at 21, Alexis has amassed nearly 50k followers and is running her own business as a freelance artist, snagging nearly all of her jobs right here on Instagram. âWhen I created this account, I wasnât setting out to attract anyone. To show you how it's done, we teamed up with @sallyhansen Global Color Ambassador, @mpnails to show off a modern #manimonday work of art on your nails. Just donât brush your teeth with it after!

1. Paint nails with 2 coats of #SallyHansenXCrayola Insta Dri in white.
2. Trace your cuticles with liquid latex.
3. Coat the end of a toothbrush with the shade "Wild Strawberry."
4. Flick the toothbrush over your nails for a splattered effect.
5. Repeat with "Dandelion" and "Denim."
6.\xa0\xa0Remove the liquid latex and clean around the cuticles.
7. Apply a coat of Insta Dri Top Coat.
8. Admire your masterpiece.', 'comment_count': 25, 'like_count': 5468, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BXOj7NwAA8V/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/20482562_847258252093597_1151928430858600448_n.jpg'}
column15:
There are plenty of unexpected tools to help achieve intricate nail art, but you probably didn't know that your toothbrush could be the key to creating an amazing splatter manicure. To show you how it's done, we teamed up with @sallyhansen Global Color Ambassador, @mpnails to show off a modern #manimonday work of art on your nails. Just donât brush your teeth with it after!

1. Paint nails with 2 coats of #SallyHansenXCrayola Insta Dri in white.
2. Trace your cuticles with liquid latex.
3. Coat the end of a toothbrush with the shade "Wild Strawberry."
4. Flick the toothbrush over your nails for a splattered effect.
5. Repeat with "Dandelion" and "Denim."
6.Â Â Remove the liquid latex and clean around the cuticles.
7. Apply a coat of Insta Dri Top Coat.
8. Admire your masterpiece.

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1563354396081885365_4073479', 'hashtags': 'OpeningCeremony Kenzo', 'caption': "âAs an American citizen, I found a community that was accepting and friends who continue to support me after I came out as a gay man in 1994. 2017 marks the 18th year of my immigrant family living in the US, and it has become clear that my family just wants me to be happy. I know this is not the case for everyone, and I am lucky to have a family who truly and openly accepts me. My mom went from not ever talking about my sexuality, to being a loud and proud LGBTQ advocate in her own community. She always tells her friends with gay children that they need to support them, no matter the path they choose.â â @humbertotoo, co-founder of #OpeningCeremony and co-creative director of #Kenzo, shares his experience as a gay man and first generation Asian-American in Donald Trump's America.", 'comment_count': 19, 'like_count': 11518, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BWyJopMgZC1/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/e35/c48.0.587.587/20184493_101528087195227_5847594468810686464_n.jpg'}
column15: âAs an American citizen, I found a community that was accepting and friends who continue to support me after I came out as a gay man in 1994. 2017 marks the 18th year of my immigrant family living in the US, and it has become clear that my family just wants me to be happy. I know this is not the case for everyone, and I am lucky to have a family who truly and openly accepts me. My mom went from not ever talking about my sexuality, to being a loud and proud LGBTQ advocate in her own community. She always tells her friends with gay children that they need to support them, no matter the path they choose.â â @humbertotoo, co-founder of #OpeningCeremony and co-creative director of #Kenzo, shares his experience as a gay man and first generation Asian-American in Donald Trump's America.
column24: photo âAs an American citizen, I found a community that was accepting and friends who continue to support me after I came out as a gay man in 1994. 2017 marks the 18th year of my immigrant family living in the US, and it has become clear that my family just wants me to be happy. I know this is not the case for everyone, and I am lucky to have a family who truly and openly accepts me. My mom went from not ever talking about my sexuality, to being a loud and proud LGBTQ advocate in her own community. She always tells her friends with gay children that they need to support them, no matter the path they choose.â â @humbertotoo, co-founder of #OpeningCeremony and co-creative director of #Kenzo, shares his experience as a gay man and first generation Asian-American in Donald Trump's America.

column15:
Happy #ManiMonday! For today's nail art tutorial, we teamed up with @sally_hansen, Global Color Ambassador @mpnails to create glitter nails thatâll surely add some dazzle to your fingertips just in time for the #FourthofJuly. Hereâs how to get the mesmerizing look: 
1. Trace your cuticles with liquid latex. 
2. Grab a makeup sponge and coat it with Sally Hansen polish in Strobe Light. 
3. Dab the glitter-saturated sponge all over the nail. 
4. Repeat on each nail, making sure to cover the entire surface. 
5. Peel off liquid latex strips to remove any excess polish around the nails. 
6. Show off your flawless glitter mani.
column24:
video Happy #ManiMonday! For today's nail art tutorial, we teamed up with @sally_hansen, Global Color Ambassador @mpnails to create glitter nails thatâll surely add some dazzle to your fingertips just in time for the #FourthofJuly. Hereâs how to get the mesmerizing look: 
1. Trace your cuticles with liquid latex. 
2. Grab a makeup sponge and coat it with Sally Hansen polish in Strobe Light. 
3. Dab the glitter-saturated sponge all over the nail. 
4. Repeat on each nail, making sure to cover the entire surface. 
5. Peel off liquid latex strips to remove any excess polish around the nails. 
6. Show off your flawless glitter mani.

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1527703824687508966_4073479', 'hashtags': 'TeenVogueMusicIssue DearEvanHansen MikeFaist', 'caption': "For the brand new #TeenVogueMusicIssue, we caught up with #DearEvanHansen star #MikeFaist, whose big Broadway role didn't come easy. âI graduated high school a year early and moved to New York when I was 17 to attend the American Musical and Dramatic Academy. I dropped out after two semesters and started selling tickets in Times Square for off- Broadway plays while auditioning on the side. After a few nonunion shows, I got booked as the understudy for the lead of Newsies. I was in the original Broadway cast for about a year and a half. It was a dream come true. Now, three years later, Iâve really gotten to grow with the role of Connor, who commits suicide in the play. In order to formulate who Connor would be, I read stories by real suicide-attempt survivors on a website, livethroughthis.org. I realized that there seems to be a general lack of self-love and empathy in our society. I hope that when people see the show, theyâll say, âOh, I am loved. Iâm exactly who I am, and I am enough.â ð·: @TimBarberPhoto", 'comment_count': 86, 'like_count': 8617, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BUzfojQgS3m/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c170.0.684.684/18809372_1075342162608123_8634843315507822592_n.jpg'}

Her account is BRIMMING with body positive goodness, but 16-year-old Libby didnât always feel that way. âSince I was thirteen, I've struggled with body image,â she tells @TeenVogue. âAt its worst, I had so little confidence I didn't want to go outside.â That changed in April 2017, when Libby began her project, celebrating âboobs and other wobbly bits without turning them into objects of sex.â She says, âIâm so much happier now than I think Iâve ever been.â Libbyâs drawings show people of all different shapes, sizes, colors, and abilities living their best life. âI don't think I'll ever get bored of drawing bodies because people are never repetitive,â she says. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1524087074872083913_4073479', 'hashtags': 'BlackGirlMagic', 'caption': '"Palm rolls, two-strand twists, shea butter, coconut oil, and hours under the dryer... anyone with locs knows they take time and care. I spend nearly three hours each time I sit down to retwist my hair. Theyâre a conscious choice, and one that has weightâphysical and political. \nA quick primer: Locs have been around for thousands of years, but they went mainstream in the â70s when Bob Marley and Peter Tosh, both followers of Rastafarianism, wore them as a symbol of devotion. Later, in the â80s, the painter Jean- Michel Basquiat had them. In the â90s, musicians like Lauryn Hill, Erykah Badu, and Busta Rhymes all made the style an integral part of their look. To many creatives, locs are more than a hairstyleâthey are a symbol of black expression. \nStill, locs arenât always perceived positively. Despite current hashtag campaigns like #BlackGirlMagic, which echoes the âBlack Is Beautifulâ movement of the â60s, locs are viewed as unkempt by some. Last year, a federal court sided with an employer who rescinded a job offer due to an applicantâs âmessyâ locs. And it wasnât until this year that the U.S. Army let women wear them. These moments, though difficult, do not deter me from wearing my own locs proudly. Each inch is a measure of time and a constant reminder of a black life lived." -  @museummammy', 'comment_count': 87, 'like_count': 41474, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BUmpR6gg8XJ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.92.740.740/18645610_645479232324374_7501782328088199168_n.jpg'}

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1513446747328979861_4073479', 'hashtags': 'HereForYou', 'caption': 'In the final part of our week-long partnership with @Instagram\'s #HereForYou campaign, we\'re talking to @elyse.fox, a mental health advocate and founder of @SadGirlsClubPBG, a real-life club that gathers girls together to let them know that if they\'re struggling with their mental health, they aren\'t alone. âFrom my experience, I didnât know what was wrong with me,â she says. âI wasnât introduced to any kind of therapy, I didn\'t know these types of illnesses even existed. I feel like a lot of girls in my community can relate to that. They donât even know how to speak the words. I want everyone to know about mental health, that it isnât something that is visible. It doesnât have a face, no age range. Itâs a chemical imbalance [in some cases] and it\'s something we can cope with â and it\'s best to do it together rather than alone. I think I would encourage women or anyone going through anything to find a friend or to speak out and seek help. Even if itâs a simple conversation with a teacher. As a person who kept everything inside for over 20 years, it\'s extremely helpful."', 'comment_count': 30, 'like_count': 13369, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BUA18xRA6OV/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/18443745_412836939102999_8672680942298464256_n.jpg'}

I feel like a lot of girls in my community can relate to that. They donât even know how to speak the words. I want everyone to know about mental health, that it isnât something that is visible. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1511178832302911710_4073479', 'hashtags': 'HereForYou', 'caption': 'During Mental Health Awareness Month, weâre partnering with @Instagramâs #HereForYou campaign to highlight people around the world using their accounts to break down stigmas surrounding mental health. Sydney (@theblackswandiaries) is a professional ballerina who spoke to us about using her Instagram as a tool to cope, and to help others struggling. âI share my journey so publicly because the thought of anyone suffering in silence â particularly young girls and young women of color â breaks my heart into a million pieces,â she says. âKnowing you\'re not alone, knowing you\'re not broken, that can be the difference between life and death. I\'ll be the first to admit, my identity makes me feel like a unicorn sometimes. I\'m a Black Lesbian Christian, who also happens to be a professional ballerina. But I get DMs several times a week from young girls who share one or more of my identities â ballerina, LGBTQ, Black, Christian â who say they never had a role model that looked like them who shared their same specific struggles. I\'m honored to be that for them, if they\'ll allow me." column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1504403097006258129_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'Old San Juan, Puerto Rico, is known for its walls, universally painted in lush, pastel hues, a city-wide mandate in the colonial metropolis. Its architecture, as well as its rich history, helped designate it a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983. Photographer Valerie Moreno documents the historic zoneâs gorgeous scenery and people with her account @afrosinsanjuan, which spotlights the diversity of Puerto Rican beauty. âFinding self-love and value in a world that tells women with Afros, textured hair and curls that [they] need to be fixed and âtamedâ is Valerieâs mission statement for the project, which began less than a year ago and has since grown to almost 10K followers. âI like to capture candid moments that come from the connection I develop with the great people that become my models,â the San Juan transplant says. But this project also services one of Valerieâs biggest passions â âleaving behind a legacy that mattersâ in representing the Afro-Puerto Rican community. Showing off PRâs peerless tropical vibes is another bonus. ð´ð´ð´Whose feed is making YOU take notice? He maintains that consistency by posting photos that have a similar vibe and spread positivity. âPretty much everything can inspire me,â he says; âI hope that with my Instagram, I can inspire young artists, especially young artists of color, to pursue their dreams.â One of his thoughtful captions on his latest self-portrait, signs off by saying âKeep creating :)â Sounds like a plan ð What feeds make you want to keep creating? Let us know who you think shows serious #ShineTheory below. â¨

column15:
In honor of #YouthArtMonth, the writer (and self-proclaimed @Zayn scholar) @fariha_roisin will be pairing young artists together for powerful conversations about their crafts, representation, inspiration, and creativity. For the first installment, she paired @yumnaa with @ohareeba â two artists who have redefined how Islam intersects with their art. Below is a sample of their conversation, hit the link in bio ðfor more. 
AS: Something I realized is that we are different sides of the same coin. Two young Muslim women â one of them draws covered women, and the other takes photographs of naked women. We're two opposite forces sharing the same religion. It adds another dimension to the Muslim woman image. What kind of reactions do you get for your work when people get to know about your religion?

YAA: Yes! We are so different! But I love it! It is so important for the rest of the world to see! I believe so many non-Muslims immediately think of a Muslim woman as one strict identity, which puts more oppression on us. Most people have a strong reaction to my background after seeing my work. People think my family disowned me and doesnât know about my work or what I do. But, on the contrary, my family loves me, loves my work, and they are proud of it. Theyâre some of the biggest supporters and fans of mine, as most families try to be for any one of their members.

Theyâre all inspirations for painter and illustrator @ktsmail, the Scottish-born subject of our weekly #ShineTheory. Katy (as sheâs known IRL) posts her finished paintings and prints along with works of progress in her dreamy, light-drenched studio. âSometimes Instagram functions as my sketchbook; a way to test and work out ideas and trains of thought,â she says. Her favorite subjects are âflowers and complicated women;â affixed with bubblegum-pink tape to the walls of her studio, her paintings evoke the post-art-deco girlishness of Maira Kalman, or the bucolic femininity of Georgia OâKeeffe. (You may also recognize Katyâs work from her illustrations for @tanyataylorâs S/S â17 collection.) âItâs easy to fall into the trap of trying to appear perfect,â says Katy. âIn high school I had an art teacher who told me I was bad at drawing. I believed him for a long time.â The moral of the story? âBe true to yourself, and authentic in your vision.â The insta-fame will follow. â­ï¸ Who inspires YOU? column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1466012530823836351_4073479', 'hashtags': 'TeenVogue DayWithoutAWoman DayWithoutAWoman', 'caption': 'Today at #TeenVogue, you wonât see our typical daily coverage. This is because the staff is almost entirely composed of women, and we have decided to participate in #DayWithoutAWoman to emphasize the impact women have on the economy, workforce, and all of society, through paid and unpaid, seen and unseen labor. Our goal every day at Teen Vogue is to empower, uplift and provide knowledge to young women and this strike is an important part of that. We have chosen to step back from publishing news today and instead amplify the voices involved in this movement--even the journalism industry still disproportionately awards leadership and power to men. If you would like to observe the strike, but do not have the opportunity to miss work, we encourage you to wear red in solidarity, avoid shopping for one day (with exceptions for small, women- and minority-owned businesses), and visit the official website of #DayWithoutAWoman. Link in bio. â', 'comment_count': 63, 'like_count': 12639, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BRYUqEoBrK_/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/17126269_1848479695373726_1521798073653657600_n.jpg'}

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1461933078233642249_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'When celebrities like Kanye West and Rihanna want to ensure theyâre always sporting the most unique looks on and off the red carpet, they turn to @DavidCasavant. ð The sought-after collector began hunting down rare pieces by the likes of Raf Simons, Helmut Lang, Dior, and Versace at age 13 while living at home in Tennessee. âI fell in love with finding fashion on the Internet and being able to buy this faraway stuff,â says David, now 26.\nIt wasnât until he moved to New York and began working in the magazine world that his obsession paid off. âI was assisting stylists who knew about my archive and would borrow the clothes for shoots,â he says. Soon he was renting out his finds to magazines as well as musicians from Travis Scott to Lorde. âIt all kind of happened at once,â he recalls.\nWhile David is sitting on a sartorial gold mine, he has no plans to resell any of his prized possessions. Instead, he aims to keep each piece active in the fashion conversation rather than worshipped as a bit of history. âMy goal is to take the clothes and give them modern meaning,â he says of his ongoing projects, one of which materialized in the form of a zine where artist and photographer friends visually reinterpreted his wardrobe. âIâm trying to turn these pieces into something new rather than treating them like PokÃ©mon, where I have to just catch them all.â ð ð¸: @colinleaman Model: @krisforreal', 'comment_count': 44, 'like_count': 10633, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BRJ1GOVgnUJ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/17076937_163035497541880_3400758347673108480_n.jpg'}
column15:
When celebrities like Kanye West and Rihanna want to ensure theyâre always sporting the most unique looks on and off the red carpet, they turn to @DavidCasavant. ð The sought-after collector began hunting down rare pieces by the likes of Raf Simons, Helmut Lang, Dior, and Versace at age 13 while living at home in Tennessee. âI fell in love with finding fashion on the Internet and being able to buy this faraway stuff,â says David, now 26.
It wasnât until he moved to New York and began working in the magazine world that his obsession paid off. âI was assisting stylists who knew about my archive and would borrow the clothes for shoots,â he says. Soon he was renting out his finds to magazines as well as musicians from Travis Scott to Lorde. âIt all kind of happened at once,â he recalls.
While David is sitting on a sartorial gold mine, he has no plans to resell any of his prized possessions. Instead, he aims to keep each piece active in the fashion conversation rather than worshipped as a bit of history. âMy goal is to take the clothes and give them modern meaning,â he says of his ongoing projects, one of which materialized in the form of a zine where artist and photographer friends visually reinterpreted his wardrobe. âIâm trying to turn these pieces into something new rather than treating them like PokÃ©mon, where I have to just catch them all.â ð ð¸: @colinleaman Model: @krisforreal

Soon he was renting out his finds to magazines as well as musicians from Travis Scott to Lorde. âIt all kind of happened at once,â he recalls.
While David is sitting on a sartorial gold mine, he has no plans to resell any of his prized possessions. Instead, he aims to keep each piece active in the fashion conversation rather than worshipped as a bit of history. âMy goal is to take the clothes and give them modern meaning,â he says of his ongoing projects, one of which materialized in the form of a zine where artist and photographer friends visually reinterpreted his wardrobe. âIâm trying to turn these pieces into something new rather than treating them like PokÃ©mon, where I have to just catch them all.â ð ð¸: @colinleaman Model: @krisforreal

{'links': [], 'post_id': '1459230964344496456_4073479', 'hashtags': 'Oscars Moonlight OscarsSoWhite AshtonSanders', 'caption': 'Tonight, a glitzy, big-budget, classic Hollywood movie musical with A-list actors called "La La Land" went into the #Oscars with a jaw-dropping amount of nominations. It was, so the critics said, Academy Awards fodder â the perfect formula for an epic win. 
But, despite the incredibly awkward mix-up of two Oscars presenters, La La Land did not take home the award for Best Picture. That went to #Moonlight, a limited-release, low-budget passion project about the coming of age of a young black male in Miami. The film was lauded for its honesty surrounding complicated themes like sexuality, drug addiction, and racism â but in the world of #OscarsSoWhite, it was the clear underdog of the evening. Still, this previously untold, overlooked, yet all-too-common story finally got its due. And its Oscar. 
This is a reminder that every story is worth telling. And even if it seems like nobody is listening now, you have to hold on â because you have to remember â some day, all of the world's brightest stars might be cheering you on. 
Congratulations to the Moonlight cast and crew, including the lovely #AshtonSanders, photographed here by @jeffhenny for our new issue. ððððððððð', 'comment_count': 68, 'like_count': 13486, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BRAOtSrASFI/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/16788522_1209220815858229_6858937135328657408_n.jpg'}

column15:
There are a lot of ways we could sum up @femalecollective, but according to founder Candace Reels, political activist and writer Emma Goldman put it best: "If I can't dance, I don't want to be a part of your revolution."
Candace's feed focuses on all things empowering and inspiring for women, but she also keeps it funny â "We need as much laughter in our lives as possible," the 27-year-old Los Angeles native says. At a time when current events have a tendency to get so many of us down, @femalecollective provides a welcome dose of hope. After all, the purpose is "to celebrate, uplift, empower, and support all women," Candace says. "Intersectional feminism forever!" â If you have someone you would like to see featured in our #ShineTheory series, let us know in the comments below. ð

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1433721738256242570_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'As Carrie Fisher, who famously played Princess Leia, once said, "Take your broken heart, and turn it into art." Let\'s take her words one step further, and turn it into action. We marched millions strong this weekend to stand up for women\'s equality, which doesn\'t just stop at the gender pay gap. Women\'s equality means LGBTQ rights, the significance of Black Lives, guaranteed access to reproductive health care, representation in the government, the protection of indigenous people and their lands, the importance of immigration, and the freedom of religion, particularly for our Muslim brothers and sisters. This weekend showed us that, like Leia, we must be both the princess and the soldier. "I\'m usually moved to post when I\'m excited about what I\'m doing," she says. "It could be a crop in on some colors or shapes that make me feel really good as I\'m drawing, a new project I\'m proud of, or the way some of my handmade ceramics fit into my home decor." Speaking of projects, Leah is also the artistic brains behind two amazing books: âBESTIESâ, which depicts the beauty of female friendship, and âLadies Drawing Nightâ, which she says "shows women how to host their own drawing nights through project ideas and inspiration.â Itâs not always easy to pinpoint  what you want to achieve through your âgram, but Leah seems sure of one thing: "If I can make a stranger happy for a short moment with something beautiful I made, I think that is enough." â¨ We couldn\'t agree more. If the answer is no, clearly you havenât been visiting Ava Niruiâs Instagram, @avanope. column15:
Ever seen a Louis Vuitton toothbrush? If the answer is no, clearly you havenât been visiting Ava Niruiâs Instagram, @avanope. The 25-year-old Australian, who now calls New York home, creates unique takes on coveted designer logos, giving them a whole new spin. âMy Instagram is a collection of absurd objects or clothing I have made which reference iconic luxury brands,â Ava says. âI like taking items out of their original context and giving them new value or meaning through the addition of powerful graphics, logos, and/or text.â
She cites icons as wide ranging as Camâron, âSex and the City,â Gucciâs Alessandro Michele, and her mom for inspiring her customization work, which started a little over a year ago. âEven though I genuinely appreciate the craftsmanship that goes into luxury brand products, particularly bags and accessories, I think it's absurd how much money people spend on unnecessary items,â Ava says. Through her playful and humorous creations, sheâs hoping to shift the way people think about what it really means to be high-end. â¡ï¸ If you have a favorite Instagrammer that you would like to see featured in our #ShineTheory series, let us know in the comments.ð

photo Ever seen a Louis Vuitton toothbrush? If the answer is no, clearly you havenât been visiting Ava Niruiâs Instagram, @avanope. The 25-year-old Australian, who now calls New York home, creates unique takes on coveted designer logos, giving them a whole new spin. âMy Instagram is a collection of absurd objects or clothing I have made which reference iconic luxury brands,â Ava says. âI like taking items out of their original context and giving them new value or meaning through the addition of powerful graphics, logos, and/or text.â
She cites icons as wide ranging as Camâron, âSex and the City,â Gucciâs Alessandro Michele, and her mom for inspiring her customization work, which started a little over a year ago. âEven though I genuinely appreciate the craftsmanship that goes into luxury brand products, particularly bags and accessories, I think it's absurd how much money people spend on unnecessary items,â Ava says. Through her playful and humorous creations, sheâs hoping to shift the way people think about what it really means to be high-end. â¡ï¸ If you have a favorite Instagrammer that you would like to see featured in our #ShineTheory series, let us know in the comments.ð

column4: {'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/15229560_1318792184821972_930129327486402560_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1390127736140148270_4073479', 'hashtags': 'AskaNativeAmericanGirl NoDAPL StandwithStandingRock', 'caption': "Two young women from the Standing Rock Sioux tribe joined us to discuss what the construction of the Dakota Access Pipeline really means for them and their families as part of our #AskaNativeAmericanGirl series. The Dakota Access Pipeline is a $3.8 billion project that would cary 450,000 barrels of crude oil every day from North Dakotaâs oil field 1,134 miles underground to Illinois, so it can be converted into usable fuel. However, construction of the pipeline jeopardizes Lake Oahe, a main source of drinking water for the Sioux. And, not to mention, the pipeline  will also require digging up ancient burial ground, therefore defiling land where the tribe's ancestors were laid to rest. You may have seen celebrities like @RowanBlanchard or @ShaileneWoodley getting involved with the protection of this land, but you can do your own part, too. Head to StandingRock.org to learn how to donate and/or contact local government officials. ð½: @kellyteacher #NoDAPL #StandwithStandingRock", 'comment_count': 118, 'like_count': 13669, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BNKuc-RDS4u/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/15047031_833290836813319_1440069471690555392_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM5MDEyNzczNjE0MDE0ODI3MA%3D%3D.2'}
column15: Two young women from the Standing Rock Sioux tribe joined us to discuss what the construction of the Dakota Access Pipeline really means for them and their families as part of our #AskaNativeAmericanGirl series. The Dakota Access Pipeline is a $3.8 billion project that would cary 450,000 barrels of crude oil every day from North Dakotaâs oil field 1,134 miles underground to Illinois, so it can be converted into usable fuel. However, construction of the pipeline jeopardizes Lake Oahe, a main source of drinking water for the Sioux. And, not to mention, the pipeline  will also require digging up ancient burial ground, therefore defiling land where the tribe's ancestors were laid to rest. You may have seen celebrities like @RowanBlanchard or @ShaileneWoodley getting involved with the protection of this land, but you can do your own part, too. Head to StandingRock.org to learn how to donate and/or contact local government officials. ð½: @kellyteacher #NoDAPL #StandwithStandingRock
column24: video Two young women from the Standing Rock Sioux tribe joined us to discuss what the construction of the Dakota Access Pipeline really means for them and their families as part of our #AskaNativeAmericanGirl series. The Dakota Access Pipeline is a $3.8 billion project that would cary 450,000 barrels of crude oil every day from North Dakotaâs oil field 1,134 miles underground to Illinois, so it can be converted into usable fuel. However, construction of the pipeline jeopardizes Lake Oahe, a main source of drinking water for the Sioux. And, not to mention, the pipeline  will also require digging up ancient burial ground, therefore defiling land where the tribe's ancestors were laid to rest. You may have seen celebrities like @RowanBlanchard or @ShaileneWoodley getting involved with the protection of this land, but you can do your own part, too. Head to StandingRock.org to learn how to donate and/or contact local government officials. ð½: @kellyteacher #NoDAPL #StandwithStandingRock

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1387832249092972549_4073479', 'hashtags': 'SmartGirls', 'caption': 'While studying environmental science at New York University, Lauren Singer realized her lifestyle didn\'t reflect her sustainably conscious mind-set and knew she had to make a change. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1387185285502377416_4073479', 'hashtags': 'SmartGirls', 'caption': 'Paige Kassalen made history this year as one of three women to serve on the 17-person ground crew for the world\'s first solar powered airplane to circumnavigate the world, Solar Impulse two. "I had just been working full time at Covestro [a company that produces high-tech polymer materials] for six months when I saw it was looking for an employee to represent it and work as an electrical engineer on the project it was sponsoring," relates Paige, who\'s degree in electrical engineering from Virginia Tech made her the perfect candidate. Having been responsible for catching the wing of the plane during landings and solving any electrical problems that arose while on the journey, Paige proves that a STEM career can bring you some pretty lofty heights. "A lot of young people don\'t understand the potential that engineering has for them," she says. "It allows you to push boundaries and invent the future." ð¬Hit the link in bio to read about more #SmartGirls who are setting trends across all industries. ð·: @cgbp Styling: @its_brody', 'comment_count': 38, 'like_count': 23446, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BNARarkBJ3I/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/14547557_214168502355715_8575537256033419264_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM4NzE4NTI4NTUwMjM3NzQxNg%3D%3D.2.c'}

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1386262500269745124_4073479', 'hashtags': 'smartgirls', 'caption': 'Girl genius would be an accurate way to describe Olivia Hallisey, who won the grand prize at the 2015 Google Science Fair for a project that could ultimately save lives. "I created a test for Ebola that, unlike current methods, is inexpensive, easy to use, sustainable, and temperature-independent," explains the whiz, who is progressing toward making her chemistry-based diagnostic tool applicable to more diseases, such as Lime and Zika. "I started this research because I wanted to help people," says Olivia, who took part in 2015\'s Bal few Debutantes. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1384808220601990153_4073479', 'hashtags': 'SmartGirls', 'caption': 'Whenever I speak, I think about the saying, Donât speak unless youâre improving upon silence,â says  Kimberly Drew (@museummammy), the curator and advocate behind social media at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. âEvery time I make noise, I want it to be really good.â When sheâs not posting for the iconic New York City museum, Kimberly broadcasts her own voice as a guest on national panels, on Instagram and Twitter as @museummammy, and via the Tumblr phenomenon Black Contemporary Art. "I started the blog in 2011, right after my internship at the Studio Museum in Harlem, as a space to both record the things I learned and continue the process of learning,â she muses. âI started looking for something like it in the world, and when I didnât find it, I just made my own.â Of course, Kimberly is just getting started. Be on the lookout for her next project, a book with writer Jenna Wortham from their Black Futures project, which will explore creativity as it relates to black cultural identity. After that, whoâs to sayâ¦world domination. ð Tap the link in bio to read about more #SmartGirls who prove that being brainy is cool. ðð·: @cgbp Styling: @its_brody', 'comment_count': 34, 'like_count': 16237, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BM3071XBbwJ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/15099567_331898097190108_3265631602729811968_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM4NDgwODIyMDYwMTk5MDE1Mw%3D%3D.2.c'}

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1382211271369471570_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'Having lived in eight countries while growing up because of her dad\'s job, 26-year-old @mitskileaks knows what it\'s like to not belong. The vocalist guitarist and bassist uses her music to reflect on being an outsider and how cross cultural identity (her father is American and her mother is Japanese) can feel alienating. "It\'s incredibly touching when girls who are of mixed backgrounds or who feel out of place say, \'Your song meant a lot to me,\'" Mitski notes. "That\'s when the gravity of what I do sinks in."\nA year after graduating from Purchase College, State University of Music, Mitski released her breakout album, Bury Me at Makeout Creek, which garnered critical acclaim. Though her latest record, Puberty 2 details her search for happiness, Mitski knows she can always find solace in music, "It\'s like a family but also a lover but also a good friend. It\'s home to me." ð§ Check out our December Issue playlist on @applemusic to listen to Mitski and many other amazing artists. ðð·: @ericchakeen Styling: @kirbymarzec', 'comment_count': 59, 'like_count': 21724, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BMumdP6hLZS/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/15043985_204712889973450_8343199612881862656_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM4MjIxMTI3MTM2OTQ3MTU3MA%3D%3D.2.c'}
column15:
Having lived in eight countries while growing up because of her dad's job, 26-year-old @mitskileaks knows what it's like to not belong. The vocalist guitarist and bassist uses her music to reflect on being an outsider and how cross cultural identity (her father is American and her mother is Japanese) can feel alienating. "It's incredibly touching when girls who are of mixed backgrounds or who feel out of place say, 'Your song meant a lot to me,'" Mitski notes. "That's when the gravity of what I do sinks in."
A year after graduating from Purchase College, State University of Music, Mitski released her breakout album, Bury Me at Makeout Creek, which garnered critical acclaim. Though her latest record, Puberty 2 details her search for happiness, Mitski knows she can always find solace in music, "It's like a family but also a lover but also a good friend. It's home to me." ð§ Check out our December Issue playlist on @applemusic to listen to Mitski and many other amazing artists. ðð·: @ericchakeen Styling: @kirbymarzec

The vocalist guitarist and bassist uses her music to reflect on being an outsider and how cross cultural identity (her father is American and her mother is Japanese) can feel alienating. "It's incredibly touching when girls who are of mixed backgrounds or who feel out of place say, 'Your song meant a lot to me,'" Mitski notes. "That's when the gravity of what I do sinks in."
A year after graduating from Purchase College, State University of Music, Mitski released her breakout album, Bury Me at Makeout Creek, which garnered critical acclaim. Though her latest record, Puberty 2 details her search for happiness, Mitski knows she can always find solace in music, "It's like a family but also a lover but also a good friend. It's home to me." ð§ Check out our December Issue playlist on @applemusic to listen to Mitski and many other amazing artists. ðð·: @ericchakeen Styling: @kirbymarzec

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1381239753156067771_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': '"For me, just by being on a show called @blackishabc, race became an unavoidable conversation. It gave me this platform to address these topics, and that opened the doors to develop my voice in an intentional way. On a personal level, even though I was always hyperaware of our history, I didnât put race in a real physical context until I hit my teens. Being mixedâIâm half Iranian and half blackâeven has its strange amalgamation of problems. The first instance that really rubbed me the wrong way was when somebody called me whitewashed. I couldnât process what that meant. In theory, Iâd heard all the stereotypes. But it was my first time seeing, Oh, wow, people still believe in a black stereotype. What was conflicting was that I was surrounded by successful women and people of color who wereâby societyâs viewâthe anomaly. All around me, there were examples of excellence and excelling. But because I carried myself a certain way, I wasnât a âbelievableâ black person to them. That was the strangest moment."â @yarashahidi. ð Check out the link in bio to read Yara\'s thought provoking interview with fellow visionary @rowanblanchard. ð ð·: @seanthomas_photo', 'comment_count': 45, 'like_count': 16778, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BMrJjzEhAG7/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/c0.134.1080.1080/15035095_676633999173058_9116690834543083520_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM4MTIzOTc1MzE1NjA2Nzc3MQ%3D%3D.2.c'}

And how things that happened before have influenced whatâs happening now. We covered Rosa Parks for, like, three days in history. But there is so much more than what is in the history books. To me, activism is a need to know, a need to explain, and a need to help. At first I was very scared of the term. I thought, Am I actually doing enough? Then I realized that oftentimes existing is activism in itself. For instance, I think itâs brave for girls to go to college when there is a one-in-four chance that they will be raped. That in itself is activism. I wish all girls and people of color called themselves activists."â @rowanblanchard. You never know what you're going to find on Carlotta Kohl's Instagram, and that's the way she likes it. Her account, @carlottiica, is "a stream of conciseness. It's a visual diary. I love looking back and seeing where I was a couple months or even a year agoâ¦It's an archive of moments I thought were special enough to capture and share," the 24-year-old says. Of course, that doesn't mean that there aren't certain things guaranteed to catch her eye. "Iâm really attracted to things that are kitsch and '70s, so whenever Iâm in a place with lots of pastels or a retro feel, I get very excited," Carlotta says. 
More than any one aesthetic though, Carlotta's account is true to who she is and how she feels on any given day. "I feel that the youth is no longer looking to the glossy, unattainable, perfectly packaged representations of girls that we've been bombarded with. They are looking for girls with something to say, girls who know what they like and don't have to be told who they are. I think the industry is catching on which is great for people like me. I've had a lot of unique opportunities because I've been myself." â¨ If you have a favorite Instagrammer you'd like to nominate to be included in our #ShineTheory series, let us know in the comments below. ð

column4:
{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14626737_373554682975546_3822202357190492160_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1358121255525928634_4073479', 'hashtags': 'quickandpretty', 'caption': "Ready for another round of #quickandpretty braid tutorials? We're back with mane master and @thebeachwaver founder Sarah Potempa to show you a style that combines easy plaiting techniques with an eye-catching updo. Grab some elastics and bobby-pins, and prepare to sweep your strands up in the coolest new way. This one's definitely not your average topknot!

1. Part your hair to the side and begin fishtail-braiding on the larger side, adding hair from the root. 
2. Continue adding hair from the root and braiding toward the back of the head until you hit the top of your ear, then continue braiding downwards. 
3. Dutch-braid the other side of your part by weaving strands under instead of over each other, adding hair from the root toward the top and braiding the rest of the way down. 
4. Gently pull and flatten both of your braids for an effortless effect.
5. Use the remaining hair to do a low fishtail braid.
6. Criss cross your top two braids and pin them in place.
7. Loosen your final braid and roll it up into a low bun. Grab your bobby pins and secure.
**Make sure you have your phone on hand, because this updo needs to be photographed, stat!** â¨", 'comment_count': 52, 'like_count': 8057, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BLZBBYVh866/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/14561750_1099712863452924_1373835101686726656_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM1ODEyMTI1NTUyNTkyODYzNA%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
Ready for another round of #quickandpretty braid tutorials? We're back with mane master and @thebeachwaver founder Sarah Potempa to show you a style that combines easy plaiting techniques with an eye-catching updo. Grab some elastics and bobby-pins, and prepare to sweep your strands up in the coolest new way. This one's definitely not your average topknot!

1. Part your hair to the side and begin fishtail-braiding on the larger side, adding hair from the root. 
2. Continue adding hair from the root and braiding toward the back of the head until you hit the top of your ear, then continue braiding downwards. 
3. Dutch-braid the other side of your part by weaving strands under instead of over each other, adding hair from the root toward the top and braiding the rest of the way down. 
4. Gently pull and flatten both of your braids for an effortless effect.
5. Use the remaining hair to do a low fishtail braid.
6. Criss cross your top two braids and pin them in place.
7. Loosen your final braid and roll it up into a low bun. Grab your bobby pins and secure.
**Make sure you have your phone on hand, because this updo needs to be photographed, stat!** â¨
column24:
video Ready for another round of #quickandpretty braid tutorials? We're back with mane master and @thebeachwaver founder Sarah Potempa to show you a style that combines easy plaiting techniques with an eye-catching updo. Grab some elastics and bobby-pins, and prepare to sweep your strands up in the coolest new way. This one's definitely not your average topknot!

1. Part your hair to the side and begin fishtail-braiding on the larger side, adding hair from the root. 
2. Continue adding hair from the root and braiding toward the back of the head until you hit the top of your ear, then continue braiding downwards. 
3. Dutch-braid the other side of your part by weaving strands under instead of over each other, adding hair from the root toward the top and braiding the rest of the way down. 
4. Gently pull and flatten both of your braids for an effortless effect.
5. Use the remaining hair to do a low fishtail braid.
6. Criss cross your top two braids and pin them in place.
7. Loosen your final braid and roll it up into a low bun. Grab your bobby pins and secure.
**Make sure you have your phone on hand, because this updo needs to be photographed, stat!** â¨

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1354641929203562818_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'It seems like each day of this year has brought a new story of injustice, ugliness, and hatred into my timelines, newsfeeds, and updates. And then, right as 2016 enters its fourth quarter, @saintrecords arrived with compassion, beauty, and boundaries. She laid beside us, held our hands, and sang us love. Yes, us. Black folks, Black men, Black women, Black queers, Black children, and anyone else who inhabits a Black body. Capital B. I am not arrogant enough to that I am the only one for whom this album was utterly emboldening. However, my writing continues, and the story I have to tell will be told. I am grateful to Solange for her invitation, for the seat offered to me, and for the music affirming what I have always suspected:\n\nI belong too. Right here. Right now. Among the worst and best of us, I belong. ð â: @smashfizzle', 'comment_count': 75, 'like_count': 24872, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BLMp6hMBzlC/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/14591949_191808964587666_7335594190681669632_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM1NDY0MTkyOTIwMzU2MjgxOA%3D%3D.2'}
column15:

And then, right as 2016 enters its fourth quarter, @saintrecords arrived with compassion, beauty, and boundaries. She laid beside us, held our hands, and sang us love. Yes, us. Black folks, Black men, Black women, Black queers, Black children, and anyone else who inhabits a Black body. Capital B. I am not arrogant enough to that I am the only one for whom this album was utterly emboldening. However, my writing continues, and the story I have to tell will be told. I am grateful to Solange for her invitation, for the seat offered to me, and for the music affirming what I have always suspected:

I belong too. Right here. Right now. Among the worst and best of us, I belong. ð â: @smashfizzle

column4:
{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14613558_329089340774609_702494261207105536_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1354596870089225635_4073479', 'hashtags': 'nofilter', 'caption': 'Weâre here with the ONLY Snapchat beauty tutorial you need this Halloween, inspired by the glowing golden butterfly filter and brought to life by makeup master @violette_fr. To create the effect on your face IRL, all you need is some highlighter, a good foundation, and mountains of sparkle. Grab a friend (youâll see why soon), gather your tools, and prepare to transform into a glitter goddess!

1. Apply a foundation with yellow undertones using a dampened sponge.
2. Set the foundation by dipping a fluffy brush in translucent powder and tapping it all over. 
3. Glide a flat brush dipped in a darker foundation shade under your cheekbones to contour.
4. Create depth by shading your lids with the same color.
5. Use your fingers to blend any harsh lines. 
6. Press a loose gold highlighter onto your finger and pat it on the high planes of your cheekbones. 
7. Highlight with a gold shadow.
8. Dust a burgundy eyeshadow on your lids and lash line to create dimension. 
9. Fill in your lids with a chunky eye pencil in bronze to create a smoky effect. 
10. Line your bottom lid with a metallic gold pencil. 
11. Pile on black mascara. 
12. Coat lips in a matte, neutral liquid lipstick. 
13. Set your makeup with a spray.
14. column15:
Weâre here with the ONLY Snapchat beauty tutorial you need this Halloween, inspired by the glowing golden butterfly filter and brought to life by makeup master @violette_fr. To create the effect on your face IRL, all you need is some highlighter, a good foundation, and mountains of sparkle. Grab a friend (youâll see why soon), gather your tools, and prepare to transform into a glitter goddess!

1. Apply a foundation with yellow undertones using a dampened sponge.
2. Set the foundation by dipping a fluffy brush in translucent powder and tapping it all over. 
3. Glide a flat brush dipped in a darker foundation shade under your cheekbones to contour.
4. Create depth by shading your lids with the same color.
5. Use your fingers to blend any harsh lines. 
6. Press a loose gold highlighter onto your finger and pat it on the high planes of your cheekbones. 
7. Highlight with a gold shadow.
8. Dust a burgundy eyeshadow on your lids and lash line to create dimension. 
9. Fill in your lids with a chunky eye pencil in bronze to create a smoky effect. 
10. Line your bottom lid with a metallic gold pencil. 
11. Pile on black mascara. 
12. Coat lips in a matte, neutral liquid lipstick. 
13. Set your makeup with a spray.
14. Have a friend blow loose gold glitter particles onto your face for a filtered finish. **Take a million selfies, #nofilter needed!** â­ï¸

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1354020754081442589_4073479', 'hashtags': 'nofilter', 'caption': "Letâs get one thing straight: No one is happier about the recent departure of cakey makeup and contouring than I am. I love seeing glowing, fresh faces in subway ads and my Instagram feed. But as a person who struggles with acne, I canât help but feel victimized by the unattainable images in front of me. \nIt's not as if I want to spend my time and money applying base, cover-up, powder (and repeat)âbut with acne scars and zits, the natural look just doesnât come naturally to me. âI think people who have imperfections feel the need to use something heavier to cover it up, but no one really needs superthick foundation unless theyâre on camera,â makeup artist Joanna Simkin advises. After being assured that my iPhone lens doesnât count, I take her advice and mix sheer foundation with liquid illuminator to mimic the look of luminous skin. âNothing will completely mask texture, but the reflective pigments will help the eye glaze over any flaws,â she explains. But, like anyone with blemishes, I worry about products that offer a quick fix but worsen the situation long term. âHelpful ingredients to look for are salicylic acid and retinol,â suggests celeb dermatologist Dennis Gross, M.D., whose Glow Pads instantly turned my grease into gleam. âIf you have acne, all your products should be oil-freeâincluding sunscreen, makeup, and moisturizers.â Cutting out oil and adding strategic shine I can do, but give up my prized pressed powder? Please. Luckily, makeupâskin care hybrids are popping up everywhere these days, and Iâve found a salicylic acid-infused compact that cures as it conceals. I never thought Iâd say this, but I think Iâm finally ready to post a selfie. ð #nofilter â: @suewilliamson ð·: @tanyaposternak + @zposternak", 'comment_count': 38, 'like_count': 14201, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BLKcrOxh-sd/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/14561760_194411807659379_3394232844946505728_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM1NDAyMDc1NDA4MTQ0MjU4OQ%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
Letâs get one thing straight: No one is happier about the recent departure of cakey makeup and contouring than I am. I love seeing glowing, fresh faces in subway ads and my Instagram feed. But as a person who struggles with acne, I canât help but feel victimized by the unattainable images in front of me. 
It's not as if I want to spend my time and money applying base, cover-up, powder (and repeat)âbut with acne scars and zits, the natural look just doesnât come naturally to me. âI think people who have imperfections feel the need to use something heavier to cover it up, but no one really needs superthick foundation unless theyâre on camera,â makeup artist Joanna Simkin advises. After being assured that my iPhone lens doesnât count, I take her advice and mix sheer foundation with liquid illuminator to mimic the look of luminous skin. âNothing will completely mask texture, but the reflective pigments will help the eye glaze over any flaws,â she explains. But, like anyone with blemishes, I worry about products that offer a quick fix but worsen the situation long term. âHelpful ingredients to look for are salicylic acid and retinol,â suggests celeb dermatologist Dennis Gross, M.D., whose Glow Pads instantly turned my grease into gleam. âIf you have acne, all your products should be oil-freeâincluding sunscreen, makeup, and moisturizers.â Cutting out oil and adding strategic shine I can do, but give up my prized pressed powder? Please. Luckily, makeupâskin care hybrids are popping up everywhere these days, and Iâve found a salicylic acid-infused compact that cures as it conceals. I never thought Iâd say this, but I think Iâm finally ready to post a selfie. ð #nofilter â: @suewilliamson ð·: @tanyaposternak + @zposternak

I never thought Iâd say this, but I think Iâm finally ready to post a selfie. ð #nofilter â: @suewilliamson ð·: @tanyaposternak + @zposternak

{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14552285_989711571138557_3606969872266821632_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1353190219587180497_4073479', 'hashtags': 'quickandpretty', 'caption': 'Itâs time for a brand-new round of #quickandpretty braid inspo! Celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa has returned to show us how to incorporate hair jewelry in the coolest way. This style takes piercings from your ears to your mane, decorating your Dutch braid with a series of looped ear cuffs. The eye-catching effect is easier to recreate than you might think, so follow along and get ready to rock this steel-studded style!

1. Part hair into three vertical sections.
2. Starting at the hairline, Dutch-braid the middle portion by weaving each strand under instead of over the others, adding hair from the root as you go.
3. Keep braiding until you reach the ends of your hair, then tie off with a clear elastic.
4. Create matching braids on the side sections, beginning at the cheekbone and braiding around the edge of the ear.
5. Decorate each rung of one braid by opening silver rings from the craft store and looping them into the hair.
**Greet the day with a âdo that shines bright!** â¨â­ï¸â¨', 'comment_count': 103, 'like_count': 8315, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BLHf1XQBtfR/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/14583350_377325422654983_7156460072657223680_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM1MzE5MDIxOTU4NzE4MDQ5Nw%3D%3D.2'}

column4: {'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14576880_345536562451195_7219626483097010176_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1352886711243693094_4073479', 'hashtags': 'TVYoungHollywood', 'caption': 'Ellie (@elliebamber_) captured Hollywoodâs attention with her breakout role as Lydia Bennet in Pride and Prejudice and Zombies. Her next big gig is equally creepy: In the inimitable fashion designer turned writer and director Tom Fordâs latest movie, the dark thriller Nocturnal Animals, she plays a Texas teenager whose parents are portrayed by Isla Fisher and Jake Gyllenhaal. âWorking with Tom was an incredible experience,â Ellie says. âHe has this extraordinary vision and eye for detail â everything he creates is very precise. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1350076502255209762_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'When something is quite literally a labor of love, you know itâs going to be extra-special. So when we heard It Brits @sukiwaterhouse, 24, and @poppyjamie, 26, were creating a line of everyday accessories inspired by their tight bond, we had an anticipatory mini freak-out. âThe brand has a huge emotional significanceâwe want it to be a symbol of friendship and of girls celebrating each other,â says Poppy, who is best known for her career as an MTV UK entertainment reporter. Model and actress Suki adds, âItâs also based off the concepts of simplicity and versatility. We designed our products to be timeless and universal rather than overly trendy.â The collectionâs two carryallsâan ultrasoft suede tote and a compact camera bag that transforms into a backpack, fanny pack, and clutch, among other stylesâcan be customized via a selection of leather key chains like the iconic split heart. As for the jewelry? âWe decided to do friendship necklaces,â Poppy says of the convertible chain, which can be hooked at different places to form a variety of fashionable options, including a bracelet or body chain. Make it your own by adding the lineâs cheeky charms to the strand, and remember to stick to tradition and trade trinkets with your other half. column15: When something is quite literally a labor of love, you know itâs going to be extra-special. So when we heard It Brits @sukiwaterhouse, 24, and @poppyjamie, 26, were creating a line of everyday accessories inspired by their tight bond, we had an anticipatory mini freak-out. âThe brand has a huge emotional significanceâwe want it to be a symbol of friendship and of girls celebrating each other,â says Poppy, who is best known for her career as an MTV UK entertainment reporter. Model and actress Suki adds, âItâs also based off the concepts of simplicity and versatility. We designed our products to be timeless and universal rather than overly trendy.â The collectionâs two carryallsâan ultrasoft suede tote and a compact camera bag that transforms into a backpack, fanny pack, and clutch, among other stylesâcan be customized via a selection of leather key chains like the iconic split heart. As for the jewelry? âWe decided to do friendship necklaces,â Poppy says of the convertible chain, which can be hooked at different places to form a variety of fashionable options, including a bracelet or body chain. Make it your own by adding the lineâs cheeky charms to the strand, and remember to stick to tradition and trade trinkets with your other half. As Poppy reminds us, âLife is always more fun when shared." ð¯

{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14487612_1771476866441093_8580314634056105984_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1348156915276151138_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'Celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa is joining us again for a cool new braid tutorial! Want to learn how to plait your mane like a mermaid? Itâs all about the waterfall braid, which grabs your strands on one side and releases them on the other for a free-flowing effect. Take it from us: Your half-up hairstyle is about to get the prettiest upgrade EVER. Pay attention, and sheâll show you exactly how itâs done!

1. Take a section of hair in the middle of your crown and part into three pieces.
2. Start the waterfall by French-braiding on one side, leaving each strand down as you weave it over and replacing it with a new piece of hair from the root.
3. Where your head begins curving down toward one ear, transition to a three-strand braid until you reach the ends, then secure.
4. Loosely curl your hair away from your face on the braided side using the Beachwaver S1.
5. Go back to your center part and do another waterfall braid going in the opposite direction.
6. Combine your two waterfall braids with a small section of hair between them, and do a three-strand braid to the ends of your hair, tying it off at the bottom.
7. Go back in with the Beachwaver S1 to curl the rest of your hair. **Do a slow motion hair flip, because itâs the only way to admire a braid this good**', 'comment_count': 79, 'like_count': 8112, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BK1nZJUhXli/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/e15/14482237_1242999299097835_4830208164831952896_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM0ODE1NjkxNTI3NjE1MTEzOA%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
Celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa is joining us again for a cool new braid tutorial! Want to learn how to plait your mane like a mermaid? Itâs all about the waterfall braid, which grabs your strands on one side and releases them on the other for a free-flowing effect. Take it from us: Your half-up hairstyle is about to get the prettiest upgrade EVER. Pay attention, and sheâll show you exactly how itâs done!

1. Take a section of hair in the middle of your crown and part into three pieces.
2. Start the waterfall by French-braiding on one side, leaving each strand down as you weave it over and replacing it with a new piece of hair from the root.
3. Where your head begins curving down toward one ear, transition to a three-strand braid until you reach the ends, then secure.
4. Loosely curl your hair away from your face on the braided side using the Beachwaver S1.
5. Go back to your center part and do another waterfall braid going in the opposite direction.
6. Combine your two waterfall braids with a small section of hair between them, and do a three-strand braid to the ends of your hair, tying it off at the bottom.
7. Go back in with the Beachwaver S1 to curl the rest of your hair. **Do a slow motion hair flip, because itâs the only way to admire a braid this good**
column24:
video Celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa is joining us again for a cool new braid tutorial! Want to learn how to plait your mane like a mermaid? Itâs all about the waterfall braid, which grabs your strands on one side and releases them on the other for a free-flowing effect. Take it from us: Your half-up hairstyle is about to get the prettiest upgrade EVER. Pay attention, and sheâll show you exactly how itâs done!

1. Take a section of hair in the middle of your crown and part into three pieces.
2. Start the waterfall by French-braiding on one side, leaving each strand down as you weave it over and replacing it with a new piece of hair from the root.
3. Where your head begins curving down toward one ear, transition to a three-strand braid until you reach the ends, then secure.
4. Loosely curl your hair away from your face on the braided side using the Beachwaver S1.
5. Go back to your center part and do another waterfall braid going in the opposite direction.
6. Combine your two waterfall braids with a small section of hair between them, and do a three-strand braid to the ends of your hair, tying it off at the bottom.
7. Go back in with the Beachwaver S1 to curl the rest of your hair. **Do a slow motion hair flip, because itâs the only way to admire a braid this good**
