column4:
{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/14419545_1269075989871790_2140643873_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1342879255067651508_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': "We're back with another braid tutorial from celeb hairstyle and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa! Curious about the half-up baby bun seen on\xa0cool girls like @kendalljenner? Here's how you to take it to the next\xa0level, thanks to Dutch braids and hidden hair accessories. Gather your materials, take a seat, and start plaiting your way to the prettiest 'do ever!

1. Section off the top middle portion of your hair, tying the rest back.
2. Begin Dutch-braiding from the hairline, weaving the sections under instead of over each other.
3. Continue adding hair from the root until you reach the back of your head, then braid to the ends.
4. Tie off with a clear elastic.
5. Gather the remaining top portion of your hair into a separate half-up ponytail
6. Feed\xa0it through the Beachwaver Half Up tool to make a baby bun.
7.\xa0Wrap your Dutch braid around the bun and pin, pulling out a few curls for pretty texture. **Prepare to take some adorable selfies, featuring your brand new baby bun!**ð", 'comment_count': 54, 'like_count': 7155, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BKi3ZFOjG20/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/14310729_285613551824172_729732545_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTM0Mjg3OTI1NTA2NzY1MTUwOA%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
We're back with another braid tutorial from celeb hairstyle and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa! Curious about the half-up baby bun seen onÂ cool girls like @kendalljenner? Here's how you to take it to the nextÂ level, thanks to Dutch braids and hidden hair accessories. Gather your materials, take a seat, and start plaiting your way to the prettiest 'do ever!

1. Section off the top middle portion of your hair, tying the rest back.
2. Begin Dutch-braiding from the hairline, weaving the sections under instead of over each other.
3. Continue adding hair from the root until you reach the back of your head, then braid to the ends.
4. Tie off with a clear elastic.
5. Gather the remaining top portion of your hair into a separate half-up ponytail
6. FeedÂ it through the Beachwaver Half Up tool to make a baby bun.
7.Â Wrap your Dutch braid around the bun and pin, pulling out a few curls for pretty texture. **Prepare to take some adorable selfies, featuring your brand new baby bun!**ð
column24:
video We're back with another braid tutorial from celeb hairstyle and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa! Curious about the half-up baby bun seen onÂ cool girls like @kendalljenner? Here's how you to take it to the nextÂ level, thanks to Dutch braids and hidden hair accessories. Gather your materials, take a seat, and start plaiting your way to the prettiest 'do ever!

1. Section off the top middle portion of your hair, tying the rest back.
2. Begin Dutch-braiding from the hairline, weaving the sections under instead of over each other.
3. Continue adding hair from the root until you reach the back of your head, then braid to the ends.
4. Tie off with a clear elastic.
5. Gather the remaining top portion of your hair into a separate half-up ponytail
6. FeedÂ it through the Beachwaver Half Up tool to make a baby bun.
7.Â Wrap your Dutch braid around the bun and pin, pulling out a few curls for pretty texture. **Prepare to take some adorable selfies, featuring your brand new baby bun!**ð

column15:
Time for a braid update! We asked celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa to show us a plait worthy of a queen. Her answer? This head-hugging crown braid thatâs WAY easier than it looks. Watch to find out how you can score the style in a matter of minutes!

1. Brush hair with a paddle brush, coating ends with mousse as you go.
2. Make three small sections of hair at the nape of your neck and begin French-braiding clockwise.
3. Continue adding hair from the root and braiding until you reach the base of your head.
4. Braid downward in a three-strand pattern and secure with a clear elastic.
5. Wrap and pin your braid in place to form the crown. **Admire your regal mane, and get ready to conquer the day!** â¨
column24:
video Time for a braid update! We asked celeb hairstylist and @thebeachwaver founder @sarahpotempa to show us a plait worthy of a queen. Her answer? This head-hugging crown braid thatâs WAY easier than it looks. Watch to find out how you can score the style in a matter of minutes!

1. Brush hair with a paddle brush, coating ends with mousse as you go.
2. Make three small sections of hair at the nape of your neck and begin French-braiding clockwise.
3. Continue adding hair from the root and braiding until you reach the base of your head.
4. Braid downward in a three-strand pattern and secure with a clear elastic.
5. Wrap and pin your braid in place to form the crown. **Admire your regal mane, and get ready to conquer the day!** â¨

We hung out with braid babe and founder of @thebeachwaver @sarahpotempa, who taught us a brilliant new way to combine six strands into one, cool style. Watch, learn, and prepare to amaze with this super pretty take on the half-up hairdo.

column15:
Itâs time to learn how to power plait! We hung out with braid babe and founder of @thebeachwaver @sarahpotempa, who taught us a brilliant new way to combine six strands into one, cool style. Watch, learn, and prepare to amaze with this super pretty take on the half-up hairdo.

1. Section off the top right portion of your hair.
2. Split in two, wrapping the strands around each other to make a rope braid.
3. Clip your braid to the side.
4. Repeat technique on the left and center portions of your crown.
5. Weave the rope braids into a three-strand braid and secure with an elastic.
**Prepare yourself for ALL the compliments.**
column24:
video Itâs time to learn how to power plait! We hung out with braid babe and founder of @thebeachwaver @sarahpotempa, who taught us a brilliant new way to combine six strands into one, cool style. Watch, learn, and prepare to amaze with this super pretty take on the half-up hairdo.

1. Section off the top right portion of your hair.
2. Split in two, wrapping the strands around each other to make a rope braid.
3. Clip your braid to the side.
4. Repeat technique on the left and center portions of your crown.
5. Weave the rope braids into a three-strand braid and secure with an elastic.
**Prepare yourself for ALL the compliments.**

column15:
Let superstar hairstylist and founder of @theouai haircare @jenatkinhair show you how to throw your hair up (the cool, @kendalljenner-approved way). This quick and pretty take on the topknot and half-up âdo combines the best of both worlds in an easy back-to-school style you need to try now. â¨

1. Mist hair with @theouai Wave Spray and blow-dry with a diffuser for a textured foundation.
2. Using a medium-sized barrel, create loose curls.
3. Backcomb your crown for pretty volume.
4. Gather the top portion of your hair into a small twist, securing with bobby pins.
5. Gently coat your crown with @colorwowhair Root Cover Up to add a touch of dimension.
**Get ready to take on Monday â  twist and shout!**
column24:
video Let superstar hairstylist and founder of @theouai haircare @jenatkinhair show you how to throw your hair up (the cool, @kendalljenner-approved way). This quick and pretty take on the topknot and half-up âdo combines the best of both worlds in an easy back-to-school style you need to try now. â¨

1. Mist hair with @theouai Wave Spray and blow-dry with a diffuser for a textured foundation.
2. Using a medium-sized barrel, create loose curls.
3. Backcomb your crown for pretty volume.
4. Gather the top portion of your hair into a small twist, securing with bobby pins.
5. Gently coat your crown with @colorwowhair Root Cover Up to add a touch of dimension.
**Get ready to take on Monday â  twist and shout!**

video Let superstar hair guru and founder of @theouai haircare, @jenatkinhair, teach you her updated take on the back-to-school beach wave. Keep the summer vibes going strong with this speedy tutorial for carefree texture with a warm-weather twist, AKA @kendalljennerâs signature âdo. ð

1. Part your hair into thirds, splitting the middle section into a top and bottom half.
2. Using a curling iron with a large barrel, create "S-waves" on your middle section â starting with the bottom and moving toward the top.

1. Apply two coats of your base color and let it dry.

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1315996353549205127_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'New York DJ @harleyvnewton never succumbed to the perennial tomboy trend. âDresses are definitely my uniform; itâs rare to catch me in trousers,â says the 28-year-old, who recently launched HVN, a line of fresh and flirty frocks. âIt always feels like I am forcing something unnatural.â\nGoing from downtown DJ du jour to working with multiple luxury brands, including Dolce and Dior, Harley became known around town not just for spinning hot tracks but for her signature classic-ladylike-meets-dive-bar style as well. Yet her itch to design clothes harks back to a time long before she made beats. âI recently discovered sketches I drew when I was 10 years old for a clothing line I was apparently developing,â she explains. âThere was a palm tree dress, and now I have a palm print in my collectionâso it has all come very full circle!â\nHarley spent more than a year researching the design processâ investigating factories, fabrics, and printmakingâbut it was her vast experience and love of vintage shopping that really paid off. âI would imagine certain shapes in certain prints and then hunt for them in shops,â she says. âI never quite found what I was looking for, so I began subconsciously designing the pieces in my head.â She may not sport trousers, but as one of fashionâs newest businesswomen she definitely wears the pants.\xa0ð·: @vforshee', 'comment_count': 19, 'like_count': 15037, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BJDW7YLAn6H/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/13687057_506533729543949_89178037_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTMxNTk5NjM1MzU0OTIwNTEyNw%3D%3D.2.l'}
column15:
New York DJ @harleyvnewton never succumbed to the perennial tomboy trend. âDresses are definitely my uniform; itâs rare to catch me in trousers,â says the 28-year-old, who recently launched HVN, a line of fresh and flirty frocks. âIt always feels like I am forcing something unnatural.â
Going from downtown DJ du jour to working with multiple luxury brands, including Dolce and Dior, Harley became known around town not just for spinning hot tracks but for her signature classic-ladylike-meets-dive-bar style as well. Yet her itch to design clothes harks back to a time long before she made beats. âI recently discovered sketches I drew when I was 10 years old for a clothing line I was apparently developing,â she explains. âThere was a palm tree dress, and now I have a palm print in my collectionâso it has all come very full circle!â
Harley spent more than a year researching the design processâ investigating factories, fabrics, and printmakingâbut it was her vast experience and love of vintage shopping that really paid off. âI would imagine certain shapes in certain prints and then hunt for them in shops,â she says. âI never quite found what I was looking for, so I began subconsciously designing the pieces in my head.â She may not sport trousers, but as one of fashionâs newest businesswomen she definitely wears the pants.Â ð·: @vforshee

photo New York DJ @harleyvnewton never succumbed to the perennial tomboy trend. âDresses are definitely my uniform; itâs rare to catch me in trousers,â says the 28-year-old, who recently launched HVN, a line of fresh and flirty frocks. âIt always feels like I am forcing something unnatural.â
Going from downtown DJ du jour to working with multiple luxury brands, including Dolce and Dior, Harley became known around town not just for spinning hot tracks but for her signature classic-ladylike-meets-dive-bar style as well. Yet her itch to design clothes harks back to a time long before she made beats. âI recently discovered sketches I drew when I was 10 years old for a clothing line I was apparently developing,â she explains. âThere was a palm tree dress, and now I have a palm print in my collectionâso it has all come very full circle!â
Harley spent more than a year researching the design processâ investigating factories, fabrics, and printmakingâbut it was her vast experience and love of vintage shopping that really paid off. âI would imagine certain shapes in certain prints and then hunt for them in shops,â she says. âI never quite found what I was looking for, so I began subconsciously designing the pieces in my head.â She may not sport trousers, but as one of fashionâs newest businesswomen she definitely wears the pants.Â ð·: @vforshee

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1315605790085653729_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'Louis Vuitton front man @nicolasghesquiere (with the help of casting director extraordinaire Ashley Brokaw) has the Midas touch when it comes to launching the most distinct and buzzed-about models in the industry.\nSo it\'s no surprise Nicolas and company jetted down to Rio de Janeiro with the latest cool crew of ladies in tow to unveil his new cruise collection. Sixteen-year-old Romanian Alexandra Micu walked her first Louis Vuitton show earlier this year and is quick to call out what sets the Vuitton models apart. "The girls are more confident with their walk and their look, embracing the thing that makes them unique and using it to give personality to the outfit they are wearing," says the beauty, who credits Nicolas with choosing models who own their individuality. French 17-year-old Lea Holzfuss notes, "He has taught me what style is about. I\'m learning how to dress." After what she calls her fashion debutâstrutting the catwalk in two shows in Paris and one in Palm Springs, California for the brand notes â Viviane Oliveira, 25, has now come full circle, with Nicolas having staged his sporty chic runway presentation in her native country. âThe Brazilian energy was indescribable," she says. Lea adds, "The location of the show and the choreography were amazing. The music made us feel like we were flying in the sky." Talk about a meteoric rise. â¨| ð·: @saskialawaks', 'comment_count': 30, 'like_count': 15355, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BJB-H7mgKTh/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/13768117_1799299516982714_679715324_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTMxNTYwNTc5MDA4NTY1MzcyOQ%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
Louis Vuitton front man @nicolasghesquiere (with the help of casting director extraordinaire Ashley Brokaw) has the Midas touch when it comes to launching the most distinct and buzzed-about models in the industry.
So it's no surprise Nicolas and company jetted down to Rio de Janeiro with the latest cool crew of ladies in tow to unveil his new cruise collection. Sixteen-year-old Romanian Alexandra Micu walked her first Louis Vuitton show earlier this year and is quick to call out what sets the Vuitton models apart. "The girls are more confident with their walk and their look, embracing the thing that makes them unique and using it to give personality to the outfit they are wearing," says the beauty, who credits Nicolas with choosing models who own their individuality. French 17-year-old Lea Holzfuss notes, "He has taught me what style is about. I'm learning how to dress." After what she calls her fashion debutâstrutting the catwalk in two shows in Paris and one in Palm Springs, California for the brand notes â Viviane Oliveira, 25, has now come full circle, with Nicolas having staged his sporty chic runway presentation in her native country. âThe Brazilian energy was indescribable," she says. Lea adds, "The location of the show and the choreography were amazing. The music made us feel like we were flying in the sky." Talk about a meteoric rise. â¨| ð·: @saskialawaks

"The girls are more confident with their walk and their look, embracing the thing that makes them unique and using it to give personality to the outfit they are wearing," says the beauty, who credits Nicolas with choosing models who own their individuality. French 17-year-old Lea Holzfuss notes, "He has taught me what style is about. I'm learning how to dress." After what she calls her fashion debutâstrutting the catwalk in two shows in Paris and one in Palm Springs, California for the brand notes â Viviane Oliveira, 25, has now come full circle, with Nicolas having staged his sporty chic runway presentation in her native country. âThe Brazilian energy was indescribable," she says. Lea adds, "The location of the show and the choreography were amazing. The music made us feel like we were flying in the sky." Talk about a meteoric rise. â¨| ð·: @saskialawaks

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1314482065923673119_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': "Michelle Terris (@mterrisphoto) is proof that you donât always have to have everything figured out. âI didn't know what I wanted to do with my life for awhile,â the 28-year-old says. âI knew I wanted to do something creative, but wasn't sure what, so I signed up for some photography classes in college and have kept taking photos ever since.â\nThe Californian photog has been snapping ever since, finding inspiration in sources we can all relate to, with âBeyoncÃ© (omg âLemonadeâ!!), clothing from the past â mainly the 30's and 40's â and working with other womenâ topping her list lately. The latter is an especially important part of her creative process. âI've been so fortunate to meet some amazing ladies throughout my time taking photos that I love collaborating and coming up with ideas and photographing these great ladies that I meet,â Michelle says.\nTo Michelle, #GirlGaze is all about a long-overdue shift in the way we think about women. âI love that #GirlGaze is helping to promote this big change in our culture that who we are is beautiful: body hair, fat, stretch marks, and all. Women are beautiful, insightful, inspiring creatures that have been held back by the patriarchy for far too long and [itâs] exciting to feel and be a part of this change.â ð", 'comment_count': 27, 'like_count': 11403, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BI9-nl7AIwf/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/13706964_1767522590187231_1629970668_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTMxNDQ4MjA2NTkyMzY3MzExOQ%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
Michelle Terris (@mterrisphoto) is proof that you donât always have to have everything figured out. âI didn't know what I wanted to do with my life for awhile,â the 28-year-old says. âI knew I wanted to do something creative, but wasn't sure what, so I signed up for some photography classes in college and have kept taking photos ever since.â
The Californian photog has been snapping ever since, finding inspiration in sources we can all relate to, with âBeyoncÃ© (omg âLemonadeâ!!), clothing from the past â mainly the 30's and 40's â and working with other womenâ topping her list lately. The latter is an especially important part of her creative process. âI've been so fortunate to meet some amazing ladies throughout my time taking photos that I love collaborating and coming up with ideas and photographing these great ladies that I meet,â Michelle says.
To Michelle, #GirlGaze is all about a long-overdue shift in the way we think about women. âI love that #GirlGaze is helping to promote this big change in our culture that who we are is beautiful: body hair, fat, stretch marks, and all. Women are beautiful, insightful, inspiring creatures that have been held back by the patriarchy for far too long and [itâs] exciting to feel and be a part of this change.â ð

{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/13944008_138300456610028_1918984369_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1312506820052555832_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'We teamed up with celeb hairstylist, yes Kendall Jennerâs go-to guru, and founder of @theouai haircare, @jenatkinhair, to bring you the prettiest back-to-school hair inspo that you can totally DIY. First up, the texturized, blinged-out braid. ð

1. Prep your hair with Ouai Soft Hairspray, then comb it back and section off the top 1/4 of your hair. 
2. Divide the sectioned-off strands into three equal parts and braid halfway down your hair. Secure with
an elastic, then back comb the bottom of the braid with a bristle brush. 
3. Starting from the bottom, pull the braid out to make it looser
and wider. Take out a few extra hairs with your finger to keep it looking extra effortless and pretty.

column15:
We teamed up with celeb hairstylist, yes Kendall Jennerâs go-to guru, and founder of @theouai haircare, @jenatkinhair, to bring you the prettiest back-to-school hair inspo that you can totally DIY. First up, the texturized, blinged-out braid. ð

1. Prep your hair with Ouai Soft Hairspray, then comb it back and section off the top 1/4 of your hair. 
2. Divide the sectioned-off strands into three equal parts and braid halfway down your hair. Secure with
an elastic, then back comb the bottom of the braid with a bristle brush. 
3. Starting from the bottom, pull the braid out to make it looser
and wider. Take out a few extra hairs with your finger to keep it looking extra effortless and pretty. 
4. Spray Balmain Dry Shampoo on the entire braid to add a little texture, and polish it all off with some Jen Atkin x Chloe + Isabel Small Circle Clips. **Prepare to turn heads in the hallways**
column24:
video We teamed up with celeb hairstylist, yes Kendall Jennerâs go-to guru, and founder of @theouai haircare, @jenatkinhair, to bring you the prettiest back-to-school hair inspo that you can totally DIY. First up, the texturized, blinged-out braid. ð

1. Prep your hair with Ouai Soft Hairspray, then comb it back and section off the top 1/4 of your hair. 
2. Divide the sectioned-off strands into three equal parts and braid halfway down your hair. Secure with
an elastic, then back comb the bottom of the braid with a bristle brush. 
3. Starting from the bottom, pull the braid out to make it looser
and wider. Take out a few extra hairs with your finger to keep it looking extra effortless and pretty. 
4. Spray Balmain Dry Shampoo on the entire braid to add a little texture, and polish it all off with some Jen Atkin x Chloe + Isabel Small Circle Clips. **Prepare to turn heads in the hallways**

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1311937150496847342_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'If @winnieharlow could get one message across to everyone in the world, it would be pretty simple: "Equality rules!" she exclaims. "Regardless of what race, what color, what sex, what nationality, what sexual orientation â regardless of who you are, equality should always rule!" The 22-year-old model and activist, who has a unique skin condition called vitiligo, rose to fame as a contestant on *America\'s Next Top Model*, but her fierce confidence came along way before meeting Tyra. "I don\'t think it\'s good to focus on being celebrated, but to celebrate yourself," she explains. "I more so appreciate people loving the fact that I love myself and not just glorifying my skin or me." But Winnie understands loving yourself is easier said than done. "That was something instilled in me from my family and my mother, but I lost it due to being bullied and things I experienced growing up. For me, it was more about finding that again and realizing that any opinions that were negative towards me were not worth my time or emotion," she says. "Know that feeling different is not wrong or negative. column15: If @winnieharlow could get one message across to everyone in the world, it would be pretty simple: "Equality rules!" she exclaims. "Regardless of what race, what color, what sex, what nationality, what sexual orientation â regardless of who you are, equality should always rule!" The 22-year-old model and activist, who has a unique skin condition called vitiligo, rose to fame as a contestant on *America's Next Top Model*, but her fierce confidence came along way before meeting Tyra. "I don't think it's good to focus on being celebrated, but to celebrate yourself," she explains. "I more so appreciate people loving the fact that I love myself and not just glorifying my skin or me." But Winnie understands loving yourself is easier said than done. "That was something instilled in me from my family and my mother, but I lost it due to being bullied and things I experienced growing up. For me, it was more about finding that again and realizing that any opinions that were negative towards me were not worth my time or emotion," she says. "Know that feeling different is not wrong or negative. We are all different!" ð·: @clareshilland

Next up, groovy â60s flower nail art for all your music festival fun. ð» **You can apply dots to a dry solid color or naked nails with a base coat**
1. Use a piece of plastic or foil and spill out the colors of your choice.
2. Dip your dotter (we used the Dior Vernis Polka Dots Kit) and apply 5 dots connecting in a ring. Note: keep the dotter perpendicular to the nail and use light pressure â this will give you perfect dots, no messy blobs. 
3. Repeat step two with all the colors you choose, but wipe your dotter clean between flowers.
4. Dip your dotter in another color and apply one dot in the center of your flowers, repeat with all colors.
5. Let dry! Dots take a little extra time since there is a thicker layer of polish.
6. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1289220020303341136_4073479', 'hashtags': 'BlackLivesMatter AltonSterling PhilandoCastile', 'caption': "In the past two days, you have likely seen videos surface that show police officers shooting and killing two black men. A 2015 report revealed that 1,134 young, black men were killed by police at a rate five times higher than white men of the same age. When we hear the cries of #BlackLivesMatter, we should not hear that white or blue lives don't. Instead, we should join in mourning the losses of husbands, fathers, mothers, daughters, brothers, sisters, wives, and partners whose lives were taken. We say Black Lives Matter because our justice system saysâtime and time againâthat they do not. #AltonSterling and #PhilandoCastile matter. Present tense. And so do the black people who mourn them and fear for their safety every time these events dominate our news cycle and conversations.", 'comment_count': 700, 'like_count': 24338, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BHkOscjgKZQ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/13636235_532833463571636_1288896589_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTI4OTIyMDAyMDMwMzM0MTEzNg%3D%3D.2'}
column15: In the past two days, you have likely seen videos surface that show police officers shooting and killing two black men. According to The Guardian, so far this year, 561 people have been killed by police in the United States. A 2015 report revealed that 1,134 young, black men were killed by police at a rate five times higher than white men of the same age. When we hear the cries of #BlackLivesMatter, we should not hear that white or blue lives don't. Instead, we should join in mourning the losses of husbands, fathers, mothers, daughters, brothers, sisters, wives, and partners whose lives were taken. We say Black Lives Matter because our justice system saysâtime and time againâthat they do not. #AltonSterling and #PhilandoCastile matter. Present tense. And so do the black people who mourn them and fear for their safety every time these events dominate our news cycle and conversations.
column24: photo In the past two days, you have likely seen videos surface that show police officers shooting and killing two black men. According to The Guardian, so far this year, 561 people have been killed by police in the United States. A 2015 report revealed that 1,134 young, black men were killed by police at a rate five times higher than white men of the same age. When we hear the cries of #BlackLivesMatter, we should not hear that white or blue lives don't. Instead, we should join in mourning the losses of husbands, fathers, mothers, daughters, brothers, sisters, wives, and partners whose lives were taken. We say Black Lives Matter because our justice system saysâtime and time againâthat they do not. #AltonSterling and #PhilandoCastile matter. Present tense. And so do the black people who mourn them and fear for their safety every time these events dominate our news cycle and conversations.

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1289094831083133449_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': '"I always wanted to be a designer, but I didn\'t initially pursue it because I thought you had to go to school for it," says Trinity Fodor, who shattered her own preconceptions a year ago when she started her own brand, @fromtrinity. The self-taught seamstress had earned an associate of arts degree in general studies and worked as a personal stylist before launching her New York label. Now she revamps pre-owned denim sources from thrift shops, vintage store, estate sales, and more, creating one-of-a-kind pieces for babes with a downtown mind-set. "I\'m my own customer, so everything I make I really love," Trinity notes. "I like to misplace pockets [they sometimes become knee patches] and also make them into tube tops - when I alter a pair of pants, they may end up creating a whole outfit." Inventive and cost effective? Pure jeanius. ð', 'comment_count': 70, 'like_count': 17306, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BHjyOtAgJoJ/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/13573359_1572778823024723_1866770842_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTI4OTA5NDgzMTA4MzEzMzQ0OQ%3D%3D.2.l'}

{'links': [], 'video_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t50.2886-16/13629349_277326185955783_1504908682_n.mp4', 'post_id': '1287752374412307232_4073479', 'hashtags': '', 'caption': 'We teamed up with manicurist Holly Falcone (@dollydayinn) to bring you quick and pretty DIY nail tutorials for every summer occasion. Next up, swimming pool reflection nails.

1. Apply your light blue polish and let dry. We used @flossgloss Wavepool.
2. Paint one coat of your darker blue polish. Try @flossgloss El Capitan. 
3. While dark blue polish is still wet, crumple up some saran wrap and gently blot each nail. The saran wrap will leave an imprint that brings out the light blue base color.
4. Let dry and apply top coat!
**Inflatable swan not included**', 'comment_count': 97, 'like_count': 11461, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BHfA_Yzgusg/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/e15/13556833_1336133956416391_1366386579_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTI4Nzc1MjM3NDQxMjMwNzIzMg%3D%3D.2'}
column15:
We teamed up with manicurist Holly Falcone (@dollydayinn) to bring you quick and pretty DIY nail tutorials for every summer occasion. Next up, swimming pool reflection nails.

1. Apply your light blue polish and let dry. We used @flossgloss Wavepool.
2. Paint one coat of your darker blue polish. Try @flossgloss El Capitan. 
3. While dark blue polish is still wet, crumple up some saran wrap and gently blot each nail. The saran wrap will leave an imprint that brings out the light blue base color.
4. Let dry and apply top coat!
**Inflatable swan not included**
column24:
video We teamed up with manicurist Holly Falcone (@dollydayinn) to bring you quick and pretty DIY nail tutorials for every summer occasion. Next up, swimming pool reflection nails.

1. Apply your light blue polish and let dry. We used @flossgloss Wavepool.
2. Paint one coat of your darker blue polish. Try @flossgloss El Capitan. 
3. While dark blue polish is still wet, crumple up some saran wrap and gently blot each nail. The saran wrap will leave an imprint that brings out the light blue base color.
4. Let dry and apply top coat!
**Inflatable swan not included**

column15:
For ZoÃ© Lawrence (@wheresfrankocean), photography began as a labor of love with her friends. âI started off by taking photos of my closest girlfriends,â the 21-year-old says. âEventually I started using actual models, but I still go back to my girls. I really love the intimacy and trust I feel when Iâm working with them.â To the Florida native, #GirlGaze is âabout giving girl/ femme-identifying creatives a platform to share their work and vision. It's nice to see spaces like these pop up for us.â And itâs not just about the girls behind the camera for her, either. âI want girls to see my work and be able to picture themselves in my photos,â ZoÃ© says. âIâm working on adding more diversity in my photos in order to help girls feel represented and see themselves more in the art world. My main goal is inclusiveness.â And sheâs bringing that vision to a range of mediums. In addition to contributing to @RookieMag (thanks to founder Tavi Gevinson sliding into her DMs), ZoÃ© is also studying TV production in college. âEventually I want to direct my own films,â she says. But thereâs one surprising thing youâll probably never see ZoÃ© feature. âI really dislike avocados. For some reason people find that really surprising?â she says. âBut I never have to pay extra for guac so I donât feel too bad about it!â â¨ Words by @hannamariehoward.

ââWe teamed up with manicurist Holly Falcone (@dollydayinn) to bring you quick and pretty DIY nail tutorials for every summer occasion. ð First up, the @patmcgrathreal pigment mani, AKA how to wear eyeshadow on your nails. First, prep your nails by taking off all polish, pushing your cuticles back, and applying a base coat. Next, use a nude, white, or black color for the background. Then, take a small eyeshadow brush and press it into your eyeshadow of choice; we used Pat McGrathâs Phantom 002 collection. While your nails are almost dry, but still tacky, tap the pigment in random spots on each nail. Repeat with as many colors as you like. Finish with a topcoat, and voila.ð â¢

1. Apply a nude, white, or black polish for your background. We used Feathers & Flesh by Smith & Cult.
2. Take a small eyeshadow brush and press it into the pigment. Weâre using Phantom 002 by Pat McGrath because itâs highly pigmented and super dense, so itâll hold its own as a polish.
3. While nails are almost dry, but still tacky, tap the pigment in random spots on each nail. Repeat steps with as many other colors as you like.
4. Finish with topcoat!
column24:
video ââWe teamed up with manicurist Holly Falcone (@dollydayinn) to bring you quick and pretty DIY nail tutorials for every summer occasion. ð First up, the @patmcgrathreal pigment mani, AKA how to wear eyeshadow on your nails. First, prep your nails by taking off all polish, pushing your cuticles back, and applying a base coat. Next, use a nude, white, or black color for the background. Then, take a small eyeshadow brush and press it into your eyeshadow of choice; we used Pat McGrathâs Phantom 002 collection. While your nails are almost dry, but still tacky, tap the pigment in random spots on each nail. Repeat with as many colors as you like. Finish with a topcoat, and voila.ð â¢

1. Apply a nude, white, or black polish for your background. We used Feathers & Flesh by Smith & Cult.
2. Take a small eyeshadow brush and press it into the pigment. Weâre using Phantom 002 by Pat McGrath because itâs highly pigmented and super dense, so itâll hold its own as a polish.
3. While nails are almost dry, but still tacky, tap the pigment in random spots on each nail. Repeat steps with as many other colors as you like.
4. Finish with topcoat!

column4:
{'links': [], 'post_id': '1273217128173297910_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Scrolling through @angelalevitan's Instagram, you might notice a sort of
theme. Dark silhouettes framed by bright, often neon, lights pop up with frequency, announcing the L.A. photographer's dedication to her other passion: music. "My life pretty much revolves around music and photography," the 17-year-old says. "I have a ridiculous vinyl collection (everything from Television to the 'Saturday Night Fever' soundtrack) that I hold very dear to my heart. Some of the best moments of my life have been at concerts." Luckily, she easily weaves her two loves together, letting her auditory tastes inform her photography (it's no coincidence that she cites music and fashion from the '70s and '80s as an inspiration before describing her work as "nostalgic, vibrant, and imaginative"). And someday she hopes to truly make her two biggest interests one. "My dream situation would be to go on tour with an artist and capture all the crazy moments that come along with going on the road," Angela says.

And photography isn't just a way for her to get in touch with her musical side. "I have been suffering from severe migraines for about 10 years,"
she says. "It mostly radiates from my eyes, so I find that going out and taking photos can be somewhat therapeutic and get my mind off of the
pain." To Angela, #GirlGaze is about giving talented female photographers the respect they've often been denied. To me, it means that we have a platform just for us, where our work isn't constantly compared to males'. There are so many young, talented female photographers out there right now that need more recognition." - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This story is part of the @girlgazeproject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1268384734488453686_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'For Kelly Geddes (@kelly_geddes), photography started off as a family affair. "My mother, Anne Geddes, is a photographer," she says. "My sister and I grew up living above her studio. I would often come home from school and mum would be shooting, so the studio environment has always felt natural to me." The Australia native (she was born in Melbourne but currently lives in Sydney) has since left living above her mother\'s studio, but she hasn\'t put down the camera. Kelly, who describes her work as "sensitive, passionate, and artistic," is perhaps at her best when shooting portraits, many of which you can see on her Instagram. \nKelly\'s favorite female photographers span the history of the art form, with the 29-year-old citing Eve Arnold, Linda McCartney, and Cass Bird among those she admires the most. To Kelly, #GirlGaze "has really provided a unique and supportive platform for female photographers to showcase their work. Itâs giving voice to a lot of photographers who may otherwise go unnoticed." Though her proudest accomplishment is "taking the plunge to go freelance," her ambitions don\'t stop there. "I would love to continue to photograph people, different cultures, and places that inspire me. To create a body of work that tells a story and resonates with people," she says. "Iâd also love to document backstage at some of the Haute Couture shows in Paris." - words by @hannamariehoward. \nThis story is part of the @girlgazeproject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. column15:
For Kelly Geddes (@kelly_geddes), photography started off as a family affair. "My mother, Anne Geddes, is a photographer," she says. "My sister and I grew up living above her studio. I would often come home from school and mum would be shooting, so the studio environment has always felt natural to me." The Australia native (she was born in Melbourne but currently lives in Sydney) has since left living above her mother's studio, but she hasn't put down the camera. Kelly, who describes her work as "sensitive, passionate, and artistic," is perhaps at her best when shooting portraits, many of which you can see on her Instagram. 
Kelly's favorite female photographers span the history of the art form, with the 29-year-old citing Eve Arnold, Linda McCartney, and Cass Bird among those she admires the most. To Kelly, #GirlGaze "has really provided a unique and supportive platform for female photographers to showcase their work. Itâs giving voice to a lot of photographers who may otherwise go unnoticed." Though her proudest accomplishment is "taking the plunge to go freelance," her ambitions don't stop there. "I would love to continue to photograph people, different cultures, and places that inspire me. To create a body of work that tells a story and resonates with people," she says. "Iâd also love to document backstage at some of the Haute Couture shows in Paris." - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This story is part of the @girlgazeproject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit your photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

photo For Kelly Geddes (@kelly_geddes), photography started off as a family affair. "My mother, Anne Geddes, is a photographer," she says. "My sister and I grew up living above her studio. I would often come home from school and mum would be shooting, so the studio environment has always felt natural to me." The Australia native (she was born in Melbourne but currently lives in Sydney) has since left living above her mother's studio, but she hasn't put down the camera. Kelly, who describes her work as "sensitive, passionate, and artistic," is perhaps at her best when shooting portraits, many of which you can see on her Instagram. 
Kelly's favorite female photographers span the history of the art form, with the 29-year-old citing Eve Arnold, Linda McCartney, and Cass Bird among those she admires the most. To Kelly, #GirlGaze "has really provided a unique and supportive platform for female photographers to showcase their work. Itâs giving voice to a lot of photographers who may otherwise go unnoticed." Though her proudest accomplishment is "taking the plunge to go freelance," her ambitions don't stop there. "I would love to continue to photograph people, different cultures, and places that inspire me. To create a body of work that tells a story and resonates with people," she says. "Iâd also love to document backstage at some of the Haute Couture shows in Paris." - words by @hannamariehoward.

{'links': [], 'post_id': '1263107082340950936_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Photography runs in Paris Helena's (@parishelena) genes. "I grew up sitting as a lighting test subject for my mom, who's been a photographer for 20+ years,â the 21-year-old says. And though that wasn't her last time in front of the camera (she was scouted by @NextModels when she was 14), she followed in her mother's footsteps and found her place behind the lens. But that doesn't mean she hasn't blazed her own path. After studying photography at her arts-focused high school, at the age of 18, Paris moved alone to Manhattan to apprentice for legendary photographer Mark Seliger. 
The now-L.A.-based photog is something of a triple threat, as well. âIâve been a singer on and off since I was a kid,â she says. âIâm branching out from solely being a shower singer to a studio singer.â If youâre interested in the voice behind the vision, you can hear her featured vocals on a few songs by @StrangersYouKnow. 
To Paris, #GirlGaze is about reclaiming space for women. "Working within an industry that more often than not relies on a female presence but is dominated by men, #GirlGaze gives us a chance to take hold and share our vision through our eyes, behind and before the lens." And she's hoping to spread some of that to some biggest names in the business. "My dream is to bring some girl power to the extraordinary cast of Tim Walker, Mert & Marcus, Steven Klein, and Mario Sorrenti.â - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This Instagram story is part of the @girlgazeproject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. I think she is such a humble and beautiful person,â Krissy says. column15:
Taking a trip to SoCal has never been so easy â just make a stop at Krissy Salehâs (@krissy) Instagram. The Orange County native first fell in love with photography in middle school and has since turned her hobby into a career. But her work is just as much about the photos she takes as it is the people she features. âWhen I truly set my heart on becoming a photographer, I told myself I would also use photography to help people see how beautiful they truly are,â the 20-year-old says. âInsecurity is a very big thing in todayâs society. All I wanted to do was help people see the beauty in them.â Though she spent much of her teens shooting for her high school yearbook or only on weekends, a photography course at a local college helped her focus on shifting her passion into something more. Soon after turning her personal Instagram into a photography account, she was contacted by Brandy Melville â âthe first step to the start of living my dreams,â as she calls it.
To Krissy, #GirlGaze âis a way to empower female photographers. I think itâs a positive place where women support each other and glorify each otherâs photography.â Though she cites Harper Smith as her favorite female photographer, when asked who sheâd want to take her own portrait, her pick is someone whoâs usually in front of the camera. âIt would be Zendaya. I think she is such a humble and beautiful person,â Krissy says. It would be an honor to have her take my portrait but honestly I would just love to grab coffee and talk to her.â - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This Instagram story is part of the @girlgazeproject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit your photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

column15:
Magdalena Wosinskaâs (@themagdalenaexperience) love of photography was born from another of her favorite childhood hobbies. âI started shooting skate photos when I was 14,â the Polish-born photographer says. âI was a total tomboy and grew up skating so I just started shooting photos of my surroundings.â Now known for her (often nude) self-portraits, Magdalenaâs photos capture the gorgeous travel locations that inspire her work. And like her photography, thereâs more to the L.A.-based artist, who describes herself and her work as passionate, fast, and direct, than meets the eye. âIâm super domestic and a fragile flower wrapped up in a leather jacket, blasting metal,â she reveals.

To Magdalena, #GirlGaze is, simply, âHow I view the world.â She shares that view by making sure that her camera never leaves her side â and thatâs the wisdom she hopes to impart on young aspiring photographers. âAlways have a camera with you,â Magdalena says. âAnd if you think you should stop and take a picture, then STOP and take the picture.â - Words by @hannamariehoward 
This Instagram is part of the @girlgazeproject project, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit your photos using#GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1247843405685744030_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Though Shingi Rice (@bluespit) has counted photography as a hobby for about 10 years, she got more serious about making it her lifeâs work three years ago after a literal change of heart. âIn 2013 I had open heart surgery and it changed my life a lot,â she says. âSomething inside me just made me go automatically into photographing and styling people.â The London College of Fashion student defines #GirlGaze as âbeauty through the eyes of a girl; itâs how we see the world and how we choose to express it.â She describes herself as a âbeautiful soul capturerâ and through her gorgeous portraiture, mainly featuring people of color, she lives up to her words. Shingi counts Cass Bird, Emma Arvida Bystrom, and Petra Collins among her favorite female photographers, but her biggest inspiration comes from closer to home. âWhat inspires me most are my parents,â the 23-year-old says of her Irish dad and Zimbabwean mother. âThey both come from very different backgrounds and seeing them work hard for their goals and achieving them has taught me that being passionate about what you love and working hard pays off.â When asked who, out of anyone, sheâd love to take her own portrait, Shingi chose a perennial Teen Vogue favorite. âWillow Smith,â she says, âher presence is powerful.â - words by @hannamariehoward.\n\nThis Instagram is part of the @girlgazeproject project, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Shingi counts Cass Bird, Emma Arvida Bystrom, and Petra Collins among her favorite female photographers, but her biggest inspiration comes from closer to home. âWhat inspires me most are my parents,â the 23-year-old says of her Irish dad and Zimbabwean mother. âThey both come from very different backgrounds and seeing them work hard for their goals and achieving them has taught me that being passionate about what you love and working hard pays off.â When asked who, out of anyone, sheâd love to take her own portrait, Shingi chose a perennial Teen Vogue favorite. âWillow Smith,â she says, âher presence is powerful.â - words by @hannamariehoward.

This Instagram is part of the @girlgazeproject project, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit your photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

{'links': [], 'post_id': '1242814909884293981_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'If your life is in need of a quick infusion of color, look no further than Lenne Chaiâs Instagram feed (@lenneigh). The 24-year-old photographer sums her work up as âfeminine, pastel, [and] dreamyâ and she delivers on all three in spades.

Lenne came to photography through her childhood fascination with fashion, but has since discovered itâs âthe medium I communicate my ideas best in â I love constructing sets and props to tell stories.â And sheâs not just shooting stills, either. The Singapore native is also passionate about making music videos, especially her âKaraoke Partyâ series that features Singaporean musicians in wardrobes by local designers.

The videos give Lenne another chance to show off her creative innovations. âI just directed one thatâs inspired by game shows, but with a set thatâs constructed entirely with pastel-colored paper,â she says. âThe next one Iâm working on features aliens.â And while that may sound completely out of this world, it actually fits in perfectly with her fascination with astrophysics.

To Lenne, #GirlGaze means âLooking at women (both the ones in front of, and behind, the camera) differently. Thinking about women differently. Often sexy, but never sexualized.â Fittingly, Lenneâs favorite subjects are other girls, and she dreams of bringing her photographs of them to magazines like Lula, i-D, and of course, Teen Vogue. - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This Instagram is part of the @girlgazeproject project, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. {'links': [], 'post_id': '1237698365391004472_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': "Even if youâve never double-tapped one of @carlyfoulkesâs Instagrams, chances are youâre more familiar with the 27-year-old photographer than you think. You might recognize Carly as the former T-Mobile girl â yeah, the one in the pink dress. Nowadays, though, itâs her daring and beautiful photos that have people talking.

Photography first piqued the Toronto nativeâs interest when she was 13. âI loved taking photos of what someone people would call âmundaneâ moments,â Carly says. âPeople brushing their teeth, waiting in line at the store.â Sheâs since moved on to fashion, fine art, and portraits, but people are still her favorite subject and biggest inspiration. 
To Carly, who cites Francesca Woodman, Amanda Charchian, and Harley Weir among her all-time favorite female photogs, #GirlGaze is about effecting change. âAs much as we like to think otherwise, it's still very much so a âManâs World.â There should be as many women shooting campaigns and editorial as men and I truly believe The Girl Gaze Project is going to change that,â she says. 
Meanwhile, Carlyâs doing her part to be the shift she wants to see in the photography world. She recently had her first solo gallery showing, âGardenia,â in Los Angeles and sheâs working toward crossing publications off her list. âMy real goal is to spread awareness. A big dream of mine is to be a photojournalist,â she says. âI want to do it all!â - words by @hannamariehoward.

column15:
We wouldnât blame you if a quick scroll through Chloe Sheppardâs (@eolhcsheppard) IG made you want to climb through your phone screen and into her world. The London 19-year-oldâs feed is filled with two of her favorite subjects: teenagers and roses. And her film photography makes both look equally beautiful, fitting with her ethos of creating an âideal worldâ through her art.

To Chloe, #GirlGaze means "Taking back what's ours,â and she tells other girls interested in photography to never be afraid to display their work. âYour art is something you should really be proud of,â she  says, âSo it deserves to get seen by everybody. No matter what anybody else says, as long as you love what you're creating and it means something to you, that's all that is important.â Though sheâs born and bred in the U.K., she cites classic Americana as one of her biggest inspirations. And among her favorite female photographers, she shouts out other young women who are taking the world by storm. âLauren Tepfer takes amazing photos of locations, like the most ordinary situations,â Chloe says. âThey evoke such an atmosphere, her work is beautiful.â Though sheâs already been tapped to work on projects with brands like Adidas StellaSport, thereâs no end in sight to Chloeâs ambition. Her dream publications to shoot for include Vogue, i-D, and Wonderland, and there's no doubt that her photography will take her thereâ¦ and beyond. - words by @hannamariehoward. 
This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1227538332967657504_4073479', 'hashtags': 'ShePlaysWeWin GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Christin Rose (@hellochristinrose) was 14 when she got her first camera, but it wasnât until she was a freshman in college that her relationship with photography really clicked. âI played three sports in high school, softball being my strongest; I thought about playing in college but opted not to,â she says. âSo that initial transition when I arrived on campus, being away from my family and not getting to do my passion anymore was really hardâ¦ I had to find my place in the world again, and my camera provided that 100%.â Through photography, the Oregon native has also been able to share her enduring love of sports, notably through her #ShePlaysWeWin project that highlights young, female athletes. â[The project] celebrates the confidence that sports provides for young girls, knowing that it has a direct correlation on their future as they grow up to be strong, independent women in this ever changing world,â Christin says. Now living in California, sheâs used her #GirlGaze to photograph skateboarders, runners, and many different athletes. She hopes to bring girlsâ sports stories to the forefront by highlighting female athletes all around the worldâwhich luckily coincides with her other passion, traveling. âIâm fully ignited by going places Iâve never been,â says the photographer, who lived on a sailboat last year. âI believe itâs the most wonderful thing and drives my entire lifestyle.â - words by @hannamariehoward. \nThis Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. column15:
Christin Rose (@hellochristinrose) was 14 when she got her first camera, but it wasnât until she was a freshman in college that her relationship with photography really clicked. âI played three sports in high school, softball being my strongest; I thought about playing in college but opted not to,â she says. âSo that initial transition when I arrived on campus, being away from my family and not getting to do my passion anymore was really hardâ¦ I had to find my place in the world again, and my camera provided that 100%.â Through photography, the Oregon native has also been able to share her enduring love of sports, notably through her #ShePlaysWeWin project that highlights young, female athletes. â[The project] celebrates the confidence that sports provides for young girls, knowing that it has a direct correlation on their future as they grow up to be strong, independent women in this ever changing world,â Christin says. Now living in California, sheâs used her #GirlGaze to photograph skateboarders, runners, and many different athletes. She hopes to bring girlsâ sports stories to the forefront by highlighting female athletes all around the worldâwhich luckily coincides with her other passion, traveling. âIâm fully ignited by going places Iâve never been,â says the photographer, who lived on a sailboat last year. âI believe itâs the most wonderful thing and drives my entire lifestyle.â - words by @hannamariehoward.

Now living in California, sheâs used her #GirlGaze to photograph skateboarders, runners, and many different athletes. She hopes to bring girlsâ sports stories to the forefront by highlighting female athletes all around the worldâwhich luckily coincides with her other passion, traveling. âIâm fully ignited by going places Iâve never been,â says the photographer, who lived on a sailboat last year. âI believe itâs the most wonderful thing and drives my entire lifestyle.â - words by @hannamariehoward.

In fact, in college she was brushing up on the law. The Memphis, TN native admits she was studying to be a lawyer, but hated it after she started working for a law firm. Luckily, a darkroom class convinced her to change her course and get not only her bachelorâs, but also her masterâs degree in photography.

And her unconventional past plays into her advice for other aspiring photogs. âSo many people think you have to be a lawyer or a doctor to be successful,â Haley says. âIf you are passionate about photography, you will be successful AND happy.â Her other passions include rescuing dogs from shelters and creating social change â both of which youâll find evidence of in her Instagram feed.

Haley, who published her first photography book 'The Watchers' in 2015, uses her own body to create her art. âI use my body as a tool in all of my work,â she says. âIt becomes a universal stand-in for my story that translates to many people.â And through that, her personal definition of #GirlGaze shines through. The photographer, who describes herself and her work as âPerformance Activist Empowerment,â says the movement is all about âempowering girls to create and control the gaze of the viewer of a photograph.â - words by @hannamariehoward

{'links': [], 'post_id': '1217399587392086823_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Itâs hard to scroll through Daria Kobayashi Ritchâs Instagram feed (@dritch) without getting cool-girl envy. And it makes sense. âIâve noticed the people I want to photograph are people who I find naturally cool without trying; someone I admire or want to be friends with,â the 24-year-old says of her young subjects. âIâm drawn to these kinds of people because theyâre comfortable with themselves and that is something I feel Iâve struggled with personally.â 

The L.A.-based photog, who cites Cass Bird and Harley Weir among her favorite women behind the lens, also uses fashion as a means to express herself. âClothing and accessories can transport you or make you feel a certain way,â Daria says. "Regardless if you dress up or dress down, it says something about who you are at that moment in time.â 

Her love of dressing up and the rise of social media both played a role in her love for her art form of choice. âI think I got into photography because of MySpace,â she says. âI distinctly remember dressing up and going around town with my girlfriends taking photos of each other for our profile pictures.â For her, #GirlGaze is partially about being unapologetically a girl. âOur work cannot be separated from who we are and a huge part of that is our gender,â Daria says. âI am a relatively shy, petite, 24-year-old girl and my work is connected with my ability to connect with the subject and capture raw and vulnerable moments.â - Words by @hannamariehoward. 
This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. column15:
Take a peek at @petradroogsmaâs Instagram feed, and itâs likely that the often-haunting portraiture will stick with you for some time. Itâs fitting, then, that the photographer describes finding inspiration in basements, attics, hallways and other hidden places.

The Amsterdam native describes herself and her work as âdriven, playful, and with a love for the absurd,â which comes through in her photos of mainly female subjects. For Petra, #GirlGaze means freeing women from that all-too-common male gaze present in much of photography. âWhen it comes to photographing women, this interaction with this male observer often results in 'sexy' work that I don't find interesting at all!â she says. âWhen a woman is photographing a woman it is often intrinsically creative, gentle, inspirational, and, of course, a reflection of the female photographer herself.â When asked to name her favorite female photographers, it seems as though she could continue naming inspiring, artistic women forever. A short sampling includes Francesca Woodman, Sally Mann, and Bertien van Manen. The former theater director encourages girls interested in photography to create a lot, even if that means dealing with the frustration of not getting  the shot you want time after time. âSometimes the flow and sparks will come after so many clicks,â she says. âWork through your doubts; be open and dive into the obsession.â - Words by @hannamariehoward 
This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

The self-professed Belieber â no, seriously, she loves the Biebs â most often uses her art to spotlight the female form. âThere are endless ways to photograph women,â she says. âYou can never get bored of it.â The 28-year-old, who cites Sandy Kim and Lina Scheynius among her favorite female photogs, came to photography in a way familiar to many of us â she started taking pictures on her phone. âI started developing an interest in photography when the first phones with a built-in camera came outâ¦ I was finally able to take photos without having to own a camera,â she says. âI wish I could find the thousands of photos I took with my phones. These photos are like the documentary of my teenhood I will never see.â And though her tech is decidedly modern, some of her other interests are a bit more old school. The Paris native admits to spending hours searching for something you may most often associate with your parentsâ basement. âI love videotapes,â Ophelie admits. âI could spend hours in flea markets hoping to find some I donât already have.â - words by @hannamariehoward\n\nThis Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Check out Ophelie Rondeauâs (@ophelieandthegirls) Instagram and youâll see that the photographerâs #GirlGaze (Her definition? âNo Boys Allowed!â) is most often turned to other girls. The self-professed Belieber â no, seriously, she loves the Biebs â most often uses her art to spotlight the female form. âThere are endless ways to photograph women,â she says. âYou can never get bored of it.â The 28-year-old, who cites Sandy Kim and Lina Scheynius among her favorite female photogs, came to photography in a way familiar to many of us â she started taking pictures on her phone. âI started developing an interest in photography when the first phones with a built-in camera came outâ¦ I was finally able to take photos without having to own a camera,â she says. âI wish I could find the thousands of photos I took with my phones. These photos are like the documentary of my teenhood I will never see.â And though her tech is decidedly modern, some of her other interests are a bit more old school. The Paris native admits to spending hours searching for something you may most often associate with your parentsâ basement. âI love videotapes,â Ophelie admits. âI could spend hours in flea markets hoping to find some I donât already have.â - words by @hannamariehoward

photo Check out Ophelie Rondeauâs (@ophelieandthegirls) Instagram and youâll see that the photographerâs #GirlGaze (Her definition? âNo Boys Allowed!â) is most often turned to other girls. The self-professed Belieber â no, seriously, she loves the Biebs â most often uses her art to spotlight the female form. âThere are endless ways to photograph women,â she says. âYou can never get bored of it.â The 28-year-old, who cites Sandy Kim and Lina Scheynius among her favorite female photogs, came to photography in a way familiar to many of us â she started taking pictures on her phone. âI started developing an interest in photography when the first phones with a built-in camera came outâ¦ I was finally able to take photos without having to own a camera,â she says. âI wish I could find the thousands of photos I took with my phones. These photos are like the documentary of my teenhood I will never see.â And though her tech is decidedly modern, some of her other interests are a bit more old school. The Paris native admits to spending hours searching for something you may most often associate with your parentsâ basement. âI love videotapes,â Ophelie admits. âI could spend hours in flea markets hoping to find some I donât already have.â - words by @hannamariehoward

column4:
{'links': [], 'post_id': '1202244923424137862_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Jessica Fulford-Dobson's career as a photographer wasn't always predestined. She enjoyed taking pictures of friends as a teenager, but it never crossed her mind to consider it professionally until after she graduated from college. Working on a Linda McCartney documentary was her first experience with an established photographer, and soon afterward she enrolled in a photography course.

Her favorite project, though, came about after some careful reading. "This all came about from me flicking through a newspaper one wet Sunday afternoon in late 2012 where I came across a tiny article, so small I nearly missed it, about girls skateboarding in Afghanistan," the London-based photographer says. "I ripped the article out and from there made my research and within four months, after obtaining all the necessary permissions," she recounts. "I found myself on the ground in Kabul, at the Skateistan skate park, and surrounded with the incredible sight of these Skate Girls whizzing past me in all directions, headscarfs flowing!â Her Skate Girls of Kabul project has since won awards, been seen all over the world, and produced a book, all bringing much-needed attention to the @skateistan charity that empowers children in Afghanistan, Cambodia, and South Africa through skateboarding.

Despite her success though, her dream portrait subject remains elusive. "I would love to photograph Banksy, he is so clever," she says. "if only I could find himâ¦â - words by @hannamariehoward

This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

Copyright Â© 2015 Jessica Fulford-Dobson', 'comment_count': 38, 'like_count': 13261, 'link': 'https://www.instagram.com/p/BCvO2NZtmKG/', 'filter_name': 'Normal', 'image_url': 'https://scontent.cdninstagram.com/t51.2885-15/s640x640/sh0.08/e35/10431884_1523827834587668_1424902111_n.jpg?ig_cache_key=MTIwMjI0NDkyMzQyNDEzNzg2Mg%3D%3D.2.l'}
column15:
Jessica Fulford-Dobson's career as a photographer wasn't always predestined. She enjoyed taking pictures of friends as a teenager, but it never crossed her mind to consider it professionally until after she graduated from college. Working on a Linda McCartney documentary was her first experience with an established photographer, and soon afterward she enrolled in a photography course.

Her favorite project, though, came about after some careful reading. "This all came about from me flicking through a newspaper one wet Sunday afternoon in late 2012 where I came across a tiny article, so small I nearly missed it, about girls skateboarding in Afghanistan," the London-based photographer says. "I ripped the article out and from there made my research and within four months, after obtaining all the necessary permissions," she recounts. "I found myself on the ground in Kabul, at the Skateistan skate park, and surrounded with the incredible sight of these Skate Girls whizzing past me in all directions, headscarfs flowing!â Her Skate Girls of Kabul project has since won awards, been seen all over the world, and produced a book, all bringing much-needed attention to the @skateistan charity that empowers children in Afghanistan, Cambodia, and South Africa through skateboarding.

Despite her success though, her dream portrait subject remains elusive. "I would love to photograph Banksy, he is so clever," she says. "if only I could find himâ¦â - words by @hannamariehoward

This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

Copyright Â© 2015 Jessica Fulford-Dobson

column4: {'links': [], 'post_id': '1197846643953001348_4073479', 'hashtags': 'GirlGaze girlgaze GirlGaze', 'caption': 'Melissa Spitz (@nothing_to_worry_about) was introduced to photography at a young age by her grandparents. Her grandfather showed her how to develop film as a young age. "I vividly remember him placing a piece of paper in âwaterâ (which I now know was developer) and an image appearing, she says. "Like most kids, I thought it was magic." But it was her grandmother who showed her another, more emotional, side to the medium. "She was a holocaust survivor, who had lost most of her family, but had boxes of images," the St. Louis native says. "She would âintroduce meâ to my family members by showing me their snapshots." So it\'s no surprise that when asked about what inspires her, the photographer, who describes herself and her work as "honest, critical, and gentle" cites members of her family. Melissa says she gains inspiration from "Individuals who donât give up, people who take horrible situations and make the best of them â and my great grandmother Minna, my tante Sophie, and my grandma Daisy for doing just that." The Brooklyn-based 27-year-old says that to her, #GirlGaze is about breaking out of the "male viewing structure" we\'ve been stuck in. "The male gaze over time has made us feel invalid with they way we see the world, #girlgaze is way for females to take control of our view and own it!" she says. âWords by @hannamariehoward\n\nThis Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. column15:
Melissa Spitz (@nothing_to_worry_about) was introduced to photography at a young age by her grandparents. Her grandfather showed her how to develop film as a young age. "I vividly remember him placing a piece of paper in âwaterâ (which I now know was developer) and an image appearing, she says. "Like most kids, I thought it was magic." But it was her grandmother who showed her another, more emotional, side to the medium. "She was a holocaust survivor, who had lost most of her family, but had boxes of images," the St. Louis native says. "She would âintroduce meâ to my family members by showing me their snapshots." So it's no surprise that when asked about what inspires her, the photographer, who describes herself and her work as "honest, critical, and gentle" cites members of her family. Melissa says she gains inspiration from "Individuals who donât give up, people who take horrible situations and make the best of them â and my great grandmother Minna, my tante Sophie, and my grandma Daisy for doing just that." The Brooklyn-based 27-year-old says that to her, #GirlGaze is about breaking out of the "male viewing structure" we've been stuck in. "The male gaze over time has made us feel invalid with they way we see the world, #girlgaze is way for females to take control of our view and own it!" she says. âWords by @hannamariehoward

This Instagram story is a part of The @GirlGazeProject, celebrating the next generation of female photographers. Submit photos using #GirlGaze and you could be featured in Teen Vogue!

Representation is so important, and it's absolutely necessary in the films that get recognized and awarded. This evening during the show, instead of our typical live event coverage, we'll be 'gramming quotes from some of our favorite women in Hollywood who have spoken about the importance of representation.

Her photography is saturated with vibrant hues, often bright, floral pinks and purples â so it may surprise you to learn that the 23-year-old London native actually doesnât wear that much pink.

Maisie, who describes herself and her work as âsensitive, fast, and messyâ originally became interested in photography as a teenager blogging. These days though, sheâs trying to turn to the original source more than the internet for inspiration. âI try to read and look at books more than images online,â she says. âI think firsthand inspiration is really important.â The growth of women in photography is also important to Maisie, who cites her favorite photographer Claude Cahun as one of her biggest inspirations and Bettina Rheims as the one person in the world sheâd choose to take her portrait. And as for the #GirlGaze? âItâs great that so many females have picked up a camera in recent years, itâs turning the cliche of photography being âmasculineâ on its head,â Maisie says.

While sheâs already had her videos shown in the Tate museum, her aspirations donât end there. âI am desperate to get a book made!â she tells us. And based on the incredible success sheâs had at such a young age, weâre pretty sure weâll be placing our preorders super soon. âWords by @hannamariehoward
